00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:32.040
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:32.040 --> 00:01:36.800
[Amit Varma]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Badma.

00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:40.240
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. Sadanand Dhoomey is an old friend of mine and a columnist

00:01:40.240 --> 00:01:44.480
[Amit Varma]: I've always enjoyed reading. And when I saw on social media that he happened to be in

00:01:44.480 --> 00:01:48.880
[Amit Varma]: India, I wrote to him to ask if he'd be passing through Mumbai and would like to be a guest

00:01:48.880 --> 00:01:53.600
[Amit Varma]: on my podcast. Well, we are recording this on Sunday, May 26. And it turned out that

00:01:53.600 --> 00:01:58.560
[Amit Varma]: he was passing through Mumbai today, one flight landed here at 535 in the evening, and another

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:02.880
[Amit Varma]: takes off in a few hours time, giving him a narrow window in which he said he'd be happy

00:02:02.880 --> 00:02:08.160
[Amit Varma]: to record with me. So my partners at IBM and I planned a crafty operation. We opened up

00:02:08.160 --> 00:02:11.920
[Amit Varma]: a studio even though it was a Sunday. And the plan was that I would head on over to

00:02:11.920 --> 00:02:16.400
[Amit Varma]: the airport with my producer Abbas, we'd pick up Sadanand to save the time of his getting

00:02:16.400 --> 00:02:22.160
[Amit Varma]: an Uber etc. And we would speak to the studio. Now if an action film is ever made on my life,

00:02:22.160 --> 00:02:26.800
[Amit Varma]: let me tell you that the car chase scene is all figured out. No one was chasing us today.

00:02:26.800 --> 00:02:31.280
[Amit Varma]: But we were racing against time. And no one races in Mumbai better than me. I'm the greatest

00:02:31.280 --> 00:02:35.760
[Amit Varma]: driver in the history of Mumbai. And I overtook a plane that was about to take off, hit the

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:40.880
[Amit Varma]: highway, change lanes furiously, took unknown shortcuts and bypasses that even locals don't

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:45.600
[Amit Varma]: know about, and got to the studio in record time. We even encountered a cow in the middle

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:50.720
[Amit Varma]: of the road. And to avoid the cow I was going at 100 miles an hour, I used a nearby handcart

00:02:50.720 --> 00:02:56.160
[Amit Varma]: as a ramp to take my car up in the air and over the cow, determined that Sadanand, Abbas

00:02:56.160 --> 00:03:01.520
[Amit Varma]: and I may expire, but the cow should not perspire. We received the good karma for our action

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:07.120
[Amit Varma]: immediately and survive the landing. And here we are now luxuriating in the elite air conditioning

00:03:07.120 --> 00:03:12.160
[Amit Varma]: of the finest recording studio known to humankind. Before we begin our conversation, though,

00:03:12.160 --> 00:03:39.440
[Amit Varma]: I think we need a break to catch our breath.

00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:46.560
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to recommend one book a week that I love. The book I want to recommend today

00:03:46.560 --> 00:03:53.120
[Amit Varma]: is Enlightenment Now by Steven Pinker. Steven was also a guest on my show in episode 99.

00:03:53.120 --> 00:03:56.800
[Amit Varma]: And the book we spoke about in that episode is Enlightenment Now. And remember,

00:03:56.800 --> 00:04:02.160
[Amit Varma]: you get a 30 day free trial only at Storytel.com slash IVM.

00:04:05.680 --> 00:04:08.880
[Amit Varma]: Sadanand, welcome to the scene in the unseen. Good to be here, Amit.

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:13.760
[Amit Varma]: Now that you've got here safely. Before we start talking about the 2019 elections,

00:04:14.400 --> 00:04:18.800
[Amit Varma]: tell me a little bit more about yourself. Like, you know, all my listeners presumably know that,

00:04:18.800 --> 00:04:21.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, you work at the American Enterprise Institute, you write columns for the Wall

00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:26.480
[Amit Varma]: Street Journal. But how did you get here? What sort of your journey and who were your formative

00:04:26.480 --> 00:04:33.360
[Guest]: intellectual influences? So, you know, I wear a couple of hats. My main hat is at the American

00:04:33.360 --> 00:04:39.360
[Guest]: Enterprise Institute, as you said, where I'm the South Asia scholar, I cover this part of the world,

00:04:39.360 --> 00:04:44.800
[Guest]: I look at politics, I look at economic policy, foreign policy. And then I also wear two hats

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:51.440
[Guest]: as a columnist. I've had a column with the Wall Street Journal now since 2010. That is twice a

00:04:51.440 --> 00:04:57.440
[Guest]: month and twice a month I look at, I try to keep it news based. So I focus on what I think is the

00:04:57.440 --> 00:05:03.760
[Guest]: most important thing that's happened in this part of the world over the past two weeks. And then

00:05:03.760 --> 00:05:09.600
[Guest]: every four weeks, I also write a column for the Times of India. And that tends to be focused much

00:05:09.600 --> 00:05:15.600
[Guest]: more on domestic Indian politics. So it's kind of, you know, it's a bit of a paradox. I started out

00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:21.120
[Guest]: as a journalist. So now I'm not sort of I'm still kind of a journalist, though. I'm on the opinion

00:05:21.120 --> 00:05:25.600
[Guest]: side, not on the news side. I started out as a journalist working for a magazine called the

00:05:25.600 --> 00:05:30.800
[Guest]: Far Eastern Economic Review, which doesn't exist anymore, sadly. And the story really begins

00:05:31.840 --> 00:05:37.760
[Guest]: quite by accident, you know, I might maybe one of the few columnists out there who owes his career

00:05:37.760 --> 00:05:46.160
[Guest]: to nuclear test. Because in 1998, I was in Princeton, I was studying public policy. And

00:05:46.160 --> 00:05:51.520
[Guest]: we had an internship program that essentially allowed us to go anywhere and Princeton would

00:05:51.520 --> 00:05:57.440
[Guest]: pick up the bill. And I chose but this is between my first year and the second year of my MPA. And

00:05:57.440 --> 00:06:05.360
[Guest]: I chose to come to Delhi. And I started out working for spending my time at a TV channel,

00:06:05.360 --> 00:06:09.600
[Guest]: but the TV channel I was at was going through really bad times. And so I found that really,

00:06:09.600 --> 00:06:15.120
[Guest]: I had nothing to do, they had one camera, they had they were just sort of in some kind of crisis. And

00:06:15.120 --> 00:06:21.920
[Guest]: so I was twiddling my thumbs. And it just so happened that I knew someone who worked for

00:06:21.920 --> 00:06:25.920
[Guest]: this magazine called the Far Eastern Economic Review. And I said, Well, you know, why don't

00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:29.840
[Guest]: we meet up for coffee, I didn't have anything in mind, it was just like just to meet someone.

00:06:29.840 --> 00:06:36.640
[Guest]: Turns out that this person who was the bureau chief in India, had planned a long vacation to

00:06:36.640 --> 00:06:43.840
[Guest]: France, had sort of a two and a half month vacation planned, and wrote to the editors and said that,

00:06:43.840 --> 00:06:49.120
[Guest]: Look, you know, I've got this guy who's an intern, he's a grad student at Princeton,

00:06:49.120 --> 00:06:52.960
[Guest]: it's just good to have somebody around in the office while I'm away in France.

00:06:54.240 --> 00:07:02.800
[Guest]: That was the summer that India tested nuclear weapons. And I was in the office. And it turned

00:07:02.800 --> 00:07:09.040
[Guest]: out that the Far Eastern Economic Review was got the first interview with Strobe Talbot,

00:07:09.040 --> 00:07:14.720
[Guest]: who was then the Deputy Secretary of State, and leading the Clinton administration's

00:07:14.720 --> 00:07:18.960
[Guest]: talks with the Indian government. And so I was sitting in the office and I sent

00:07:20.240 --> 00:07:26.640
[Guest]: honest, but carefully crafted facts to just one Singh's office, where I said factually,

00:07:27.280 --> 00:07:31.760
[Guest]: that I worked with the Far Eastern Economic, I was writing for the Far Eastern Economic Review,

00:07:31.760 --> 00:07:37.520
[Guest]: I was visiting from the United States. And our magazine had just done an interview with Strobe

00:07:37.520 --> 00:07:44.080
[Guest]: Talbot. And would he be interested in telling us about the Indian side of the story. And at this

00:07:44.080 --> 00:07:49.280
[Guest]: point, just one thing had not spoken to anyone. And so I walk into his office, and I'm wearing

00:07:49.280 --> 00:07:54.960
[Guest]: these sandals. And I walk in and he sort of looks at me and I look way too young to be the person he

00:07:54.960 --> 00:07:58.960
[Guest]: was be talking to. And he said, Well, you know, tell me about yourself. What are you doing over

00:07:58.960 --> 00:08:04.880
[Guest]: here? And I told her actually, I'm the intern, I'm just visiting from Princeton. But to his credit,

00:08:04.880 --> 00:08:12.240
[Guest]: he didn't turn me out. He sat down, he did the interview. It was a bit of a scoop at the time.

00:08:13.280 --> 00:08:18.800
[Guest]: And then from there, I just spent, you know, the next several weeks churning out stories,

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:22.320
[Guest]: because I mean, this is sort of heaven for me. I mean, I would have paid them to be

00:08:22.320 --> 00:08:28.000
[Guest]: doing what I was doing. And I went back to Princeton after that. And when it was time to

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:35.040
[Guest]: when it was time to graduate, someone had from a magazine had sort of made me an offer. And I

00:08:35.040 --> 00:08:40.960
[Guest]: wrote to the editors of the review asking for a recommendation, because I'd spent the summer there.

00:08:40.960 --> 00:08:46.880
[Guest]: And instead, I was given a job offer. And I became the India bureau chief of the Far Eastern

00:08:46.880 --> 00:08:52.800
[Guest]: Economic Review, a year after I'd been the intern, did that for a bit. And in those days,

00:08:52.800 --> 00:08:58.480
[Guest]: it kind of tells you how, you know, time how Asia has changed. But in those days, for us,

00:08:59.280 --> 00:09:06.160
[Guest]: Southeast Asia was much, much more important than India. It was just a bigger story. And so

00:09:06.160 --> 00:09:10.160
[Guest]: I was cranking out stories, I had a story, sometimes two stories every week, it was a

00:09:10.160 --> 00:09:15.040
[Guest]: weekly magazine. And my editors in Hong Kong said that, you know, you're incredibly productive.

00:09:15.040 --> 00:09:18.480
[Guest]: And we don't want to waste you in India, because really, who cares about the India story?

00:09:18.480 --> 00:09:22.720
[Guest]: Where we, you know, why don't we send you to someplace in Southeast Asia? Or where would

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:28.560
[Guest]: you like to go? And I picked Indonesia, because for two reasons. One, I'd lived there as a child.

00:09:29.440 --> 00:09:35.680
[Guest]: And secondly, as an Indian, I had a bit of this big country bias. So you know, it's just sort of

00:09:35.680 --> 00:09:43.120
[Guest]: hard for me to get extremely enthusiastic about Malaysia or Thailand or any of the whereas

00:09:43.120 --> 00:09:47.280
[Guest]: Indonesia was a serious country, more than 200 million people and so on. So I ended up in

00:09:47.280 --> 00:09:54.000
[Guest]: Indonesia for four years. I was there during the Bali bombings of 2002. And I ended up writing a

00:09:54.000 --> 00:10:01.920
[Guest]: book about the rise of radical Islam in Indonesia. And then for a while I was after the book,

00:10:01.920 --> 00:10:11.280
[Guest]: I was just freelancing, doing my own thing. And again, just by accident, I wrote something in

00:10:11.280 --> 00:10:17.920
[Guest]: the Wall Street Journal, I happened to be in New York, the day that Faisal Shahzad tried to blow

00:10:17.920 --> 00:10:23.200
[Guest]: up Times Square, and it didn't didn't work out. And I wrote a piece the next day, about how,

00:10:23.200 --> 00:10:27.920
[Guest]: you know, the reason why historical reasons, Pakistan, this is then not, it's no longer true

00:10:27.920 --> 00:10:34.480
[Guest]: today, Pakistan produced such a large proportion of the world's jihadists. And this ended up being

00:10:34.480 --> 00:10:41.440
[Guest]: blogged about on AEI's website. One thing led to the other, I went there for lunch just to meet

00:10:41.440 --> 00:10:46.320
[Guest]: some people I didn't again, didn't have any idea that there was a job in the works. And by the end

00:10:46.320 --> 00:10:53.440
[Guest]: of the lunch, I was offered a position as their South Asia scholar. And so that's sort of been the

00:10:53.440 --> 00:10:59.840
[Guest]: I mean, it's been a series of accidents. I still sort of think of myself in many ways as a reporter.

00:10:59.840 --> 00:11:06.720
[Guest]: And in many ways, Columbia Journalism School was as important to me as formative to me as

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:13.120
[Guest]: Princeton and public policy. And Princeton and the public policy school was, you know, all about

00:11:13.680 --> 00:11:17.200
[Guest]: getting a grounding in macroeconomics and microeconomics and international relations

00:11:17.200 --> 00:11:23.440
[Guest]: and so on, you know, standard neoliberal dogma. But the journalism school was really about,

00:11:23.440 --> 00:11:27.280
[Guest]: you know, that was in some ways, that was a very artisanal, it was about craft.

00:11:27.280 --> 00:11:32.880
[Guest]: And I cared a lot about that. And at the time, when I went to journalism school,

00:11:33.680 --> 00:11:37.920
[Guest]: that's what I was really interested in. And if I hadn't gone to policy school,

00:11:38.480 --> 00:11:44.800
[Guest]: I would probably have gone to an MFA, and I would have done a writing class. So I wasn't sort of I

00:11:44.800 --> 00:11:50.560
[Guest]: didn't start out necessarily with a, with a wonkish bent, but then just sort of one thing

00:11:50.560 --> 00:11:55.680
[Guest]: led to the other. And, and that's how it is. In fact, we first met when your book,

00:11:55.680 --> 00:11:59.520
[Amit Varma]: My Friend the Fanatic launched in India. If you remember, we have, you know, I did the Bombay

00:11:59.520 --> 00:12:05.440
[Amit Varma]: launch. Absolutely. We had a panel discussion about it panel as in me interviewing you. So

00:12:05.440 --> 00:12:12.000
[Amit Varma]: this is like a revisitation. And that was what 2010 now, something like that ages ago. Yeah,

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:16.880
[Amit Varma]: maybe in 2009, even. So what were kind of your, you know, through this period,

00:12:16.880 --> 00:12:20.640
[Amit Varma]: you went to both Columbia did journalism, you did public policy in Princeton, what were like

00:12:20.640 --> 00:12:24.640
[Amit Varma]: your formative intellectual influences? Like, have you changed along the way?

00:12:24.640 --> 00:12:32.320
[Amit Varma]: If I like one question I ask a lot of my guests is, can you name a book or maybe multiple books

00:12:32.320 --> 00:12:37.040
[Amit Varma]: that changed the way you think about the world? And would it be easy for you to pinpoint that?

00:12:37.680 --> 00:12:41.040
[Guest]: Actually, wouldn't be maybe it's been because I've been spending too much time in TV studios

00:12:41.040 --> 00:12:47.600
[Guest]: right now. It wouldn't be easy for me to pinpoint, you know, one or two books in particular,

00:12:48.240 --> 00:12:53.280
[Guest]: I would say that in many ways, my you know, what was formative to me was more than anything else,

00:12:53.280 --> 00:12:59.920
[Guest]: my work as a journalist. And I found the Indonesia experience was extremely important for me.

00:13:00.640 --> 00:13:06.080
[Guest]: Because I had, you know, like many Indians who had studied in the United States,

00:13:06.800 --> 00:13:12.480
[Guest]: I had not been surprised by the disparity in wealth and development. That's what you expect

00:13:12.480 --> 00:13:19.280
[Guest]: when you go from Delhi to New York. And that was very normal. And it was only when I moved to

00:13:19.280 --> 00:13:25.360
[Guest]: Indonesia, which was also a developing country. And I saw just how much better Indonesia had done.

00:13:25.360 --> 00:13:32.640
[Guest]: We're talking about the late 1990s. In fact, I landed in Indonesia in 2000. You sort of realize

00:13:32.640 --> 00:13:36.640
[Guest]: that even though Indonesia was in the midst of the financial crisis, right, it still hadn't

00:13:36.640 --> 00:13:42.720
[Guest]: recovered from the 1997 Asian financial crisis, three years later, it had done so much better by

00:13:42.720 --> 00:13:49.280
[Guest]: its people. And so a lot of the sort of a lot of my reading was, you know, around the East Asian

00:13:49.280 --> 00:13:56.640
[Guest]: miracle, around development, a lot about politics in Southeast Asia, politics in, in Indonesia,

00:13:56.640 --> 00:14:04.160
[Guest]: in particular. So all of that was sort of part of it, I wouldn't say, you know, any one particular

00:14:04.800 --> 00:14:10.960
[Guest]: writer from that period sort of stands out for me. But certainly in terms of my experience,

00:14:10.960 --> 00:14:18.160
[Guest]: the travel, and the experience of living in another country and culture, immersing myself in it,

00:14:18.160 --> 00:14:22.160
[Guest]: and really having to report on it from day one, right, which is what you do as a journalist,

00:14:22.160 --> 00:14:26.880
[Guest]: you're just thrown into the deep end and you're sort of start making sense of this. That was

00:14:26.880 --> 00:14:32.880
[Amit Varma]: extremely influential for me. And what did you learn from your experiences there about what we

00:14:32.880 --> 00:14:36.560
[Amit Varma]: were doing wrong? Like what were they doing? Right? What were we doing wrong? What were the sort of

00:14:36.560 --> 00:14:42.000
[Guest]: the directions in which we needed to go? So if you think about it, Suharto and Indira Gandhi

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:48.720
[Guest]: were almost exact contemporaries. Indira Gandhi took power in 1966. And Suharto, after the bloody

00:14:48.720 --> 00:14:56.000
[Guest]: killings of the communists in Indonesia, basically took power at the same time. And the difference is

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:03.120
[Guest]: that Indira Gandhi doubled down on state planning, socialism, in fact, she deepened some of the

00:15:03.120 --> 00:15:07.520
[Guest]: errors that we had already made in the early years after independence, whereas Suharto,

00:15:08.560 --> 00:15:14.240
[Guest]: with the Americans holding his hand, brought in some economists from Berkeley, very similar to

00:15:14.240 --> 00:15:19.520
[Guest]: the Chilean story, right? You had the Chicago boys in Chile, you had the Berkeley gang in Indonesia,

00:15:20.240 --> 00:15:26.480
[Guest]: and allowed the market to play a greater role in the economy, rationalized economic decision making,

00:15:26.480 --> 00:15:33.120
[Guest]: allowed the private sector to flourish. And as a result, Indonesia really began to pull away. And

00:15:33.120 --> 00:15:37.360
[Guest]: even today, you know, so many years after we started our reform program here in India,

00:15:37.920 --> 00:15:43.040
[Guest]: the Indonesians still remain, you know, it remains a country, which is the higher per capita income,

00:15:43.040 --> 00:15:47.600
[Guest]: higher human development indicators, and so on. And it's not as though the Indonesian reform

00:15:47.600 --> 00:15:53.760
[Guest]: story has been perfect. In many ways, it's been, it's had its share of flaws. But the central

00:15:53.760 --> 00:16:02.240
[Guest]: difference between Indonesia and India was that by the 1970s, the Indonesians had decided to trust

00:16:02.240 --> 00:16:06.880
[Guest]: at least to a degree, the invisible hand of the market, whereas through the 1970s,

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:09.040
[Guest]: India was still trusting the heavy hand of the state.

00:16:10.160 --> 00:16:17.360
[Amit Varma]: Right. And how relevant does this then become, for example, to how one looks at Narendra Modi,

00:16:17.360 --> 00:16:24.080
[Amit Varma]: for example, who we are discussing today, in the sense that there is one narrative arc, which talks

00:16:24.080 --> 00:16:28.720
[Amit Varma]: about the rise of Hindutva, right from the Jansangh onwards, and you know, the BJP getting

00:16:28.720 --> 00:16:34.560
[Amit Varma]: four seats in 1984, then the whole Ayodhya thing happening and being the impetus for their growth,

00:16:34.560 --> 00:16:41.600
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth. But at the same time, a lot of people also turned to the BJP, hopefully,

00:16:41.600 --> 00:16:45.760
[Amit Varma]: because they were so disheartened by the heavy hand of the state, which despite the partial

00:16:45.760 --> 00:16:52.720
[Amit Varma]: liberalization of 91, the Congress still seemed to believe in, and in many ways, watch by as Prime

00:16:52.720 --> 00:16:57.040
[Amit Varma]: Minister did carry out a bunch of reforms and hold out hope that India could move further in

00:16:57.040 --> 00:17:03.280
[Amit Varma]: the direction. And was that also then a parallel impetus behind the support that Modi got from a

00:17:03.280 --> 00:17:08.640
[Guest]: lot of people despite the riots of 2002? I'm not sure if I'd say it's a lot, right? I mean,

00:17:08.640 --> 00:17:15.920
[Guest]: I would divide this, you know, between sort of elite opinion makers, people writing in the pink

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:23.120
[Guest]: pages, and your average guy on the street. And at some level, that development story or the hope of

00:17:23.120 --> 00:17:33.280
[Guest]: development story does intersect. But it was only a handful of commentators, who essentially took

00:17:33.280 --> 00:17:40.560
[Guest]: the call on Modi and said, here is the person who is most likely to pick up the mantle of the

00:17:40.560 --> 00:17:46.480
[Guest]: Vajpayee era reforms. We'd seen them languish for 10 years under Manmohan Singh, despite Manmohan

00:17:46.480 --> 00:17:52.720
[Guest]: Singh's own credentials, as the finance minister who kickstarted liberalization in 1991. And so we

00:17:52.720 --> 00:17:57.120
[Guest]: had, you know, obviously, you know, we've talked about this before, you know, there was a schism

00:17:57.120 --> 00:18:04.320
[Guest]: among those of us who have long argued for a greater role for the market in the Indian economy.

00:18:04.880 --> 00:18:11.760
[Guest]: And some people felt that because of 2002, and because of the baggage that Modi carried,

00:18:11.760 --> 00:18:17.600
[Guest]: he should never be allowed to should never be supported for the top job. That was, in fact,

00:18:17.600 --> 00:18:26.080
[Guest]: my position also until around the middle of 2013, when he became the party nominee. Once I sort of

00:18:26.080 --> 00:18:31.840
[Guest]: saw it mentally as a primary process, he was not the person I would have liked to see win that

00:18:31.840 --> 00:18:38.560
[Guest]: primary, though, I did think that his stewardship of Gujarat did give him a claim to perhaps have

00:18:38.560 --> 00:18:44.560
[Guest]: an outside influence, outside influence in running the economy. After 2013, when he became the

00:18:44.560 --> 00:18:51.120
[Guest]: candidate, I thought that this was the best bet. He was the best bet for, for reform. Now, that

00:18:51.120 --> 00:18:57.200
[Guest]: was a sort of conversation that was being had, as I said, on the op ed pages and in television

00:18:57.200 --> 00:19:03.600
[Guest]: studios, and so on. On the ground, it was obviously not a converse, this was not this kind of

00:19:03.600 --> 00:19:11.360
[Guest]: conversation, right? I mean, I remember I was in Varanasi for his election in 2014. And I went to

00:19:11.360 --> 00:19:17.200
[Guest]: an English teaching class. And these were just, you know, mostly young people, obviously people

00:19:17.200 --> 00:19:21.520
[Guest]: who did not speak English, as a first language, they were trying to learn English as adults.

00:19:22.240 --> 00:19:28.000
[Guest]: And I asked the teacher was very kind, he sort of let me just chat with the students. And I asked

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:32.640
[Guest]: them, so these are people not necessarily, so they'd be from the age group would be, you know,

00:19:32.640 --> 00:19:38.480
[Guest]: roughly from 18 to 28. So many of them were working people who are then coming in to sort

00:19:38.480 --> 00:19:46.960
[Guest]: of improve their English. And I asked them who they would vote for. And the overwhelming majority

00:19:46.960 --> 00:19:52.240
[Guest]: picked Modi. Oddly enough, a few of them picked Aam Aadmi Party, which seems so quaint now,

00:19:53.360 --> 00:20:00.000
[Unknown]: five years later, but most of them picked Modi. And the reasons were very sort of basic. It was

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:06.400
[Guest]: like, someone said that he had a brother who worked in Gujarat, and he had gone to visit his

00:20:06.400 --> 00:20:12.000
[Guest]: brother and he found that in Gujarat, they didn't have power cuts, but they had power cuts in UP.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:16.960
[Guest]: Someone else had, you know, showed me a photo, it turned out to be some precursor to the fake

00:20:16.960 --> 00:20:22.160
[Guest]: news flood, we'd seen it turned out to be a photo from China, but it was, look, this is some bus

00:20:22.160 --> 00:20:30.560
[Guest]: stop that Modi ji has created in Gujarat. But it was sort of very, very concrete reasons, right?

00:20:30.560 --> 00:20:35.360
[Guest]: So people just had a sense that India things are not moving. And it's certainly true that you know,

00:20:35.360 --> 00:20:42.560
[Guest]: the pundits, we may have fed that on the periphery. But I don't think that elite level conversation

00:20:42.560 --> 00:20:48.080
[Guest]: that wonkish conversation to had was the same conversation that the masses were having.

00:20:48.640 --> 00:20:53.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And there was a recent caravan story on you and a bunch of others who, you know,

00:20:53.840 --> 00:20:58.640
[Amit Varma]: criticizing you guys for supporting Modi in 2014. And then changing your minds as if changing your

00:20:58.640 --> 00:21:03.760
[Amit Varma]: mind is a bad thing when the facts change. And the way I look at it is that, in some senses,

00:21:03.760 --> 00:21:08.400
[Amit Varma]: that kind of judgment comes from the tyranny of history in the sense that whatever has happened

00:21:08.400 --> 00:21:14.240
[Amit Varma]: in the past seems inevitable after it happens. But in 2014, it would certainly not have been

00:21:14.240 --> 00:21:20.640
[Amit Varma]: inevitable that it will necessarily pan out this way. And I think the bet that a lot of people made

00:21:20.640 --> 00:21:27.760
[Amit Varma]: was that he can either carry on consolidating his power and actually follow through on some of his

00:21:27.760 --> 00:21:32.960
[Amit Varma]: development rhetoric, and leave the Hindutva behind, which for a lot of the time he had done

00:21:32.960 --> 00:21:37.520
[Amit Varma]: he had done in Gujarat, where he sidelined the RSS guys like Gurdan Tafadia, sidelined the VHP

00:21:37.520 --> 00:21:42.960
[Amit Varma]: and so on. Or he could ignore the development and go for Hindutva. And of course, as we know,

00:21:42.960 --> 00:21:47.920
[Amit Varma]: what has happened is that economically, the last five years have been pretty much a disaster and

00:21:47.920 --> 00:21:53.440
[Amit Varma]: society is more polarized than ever. And it's gone in that way, but it need not have gone in that

00:21:53.440 --> 00:21:57.520
[Amit Varma]: way. And with the benefit of hindsight to now sort of look back and say that, oh, you should

00:21:57.520 --> 00:22:01.520
[Guest]: have known this all along, I think is somewhat unfair. Yeah, I think it's perfectly okay for

00:22:01.520 --> 00:22:07.200
[Guest]: the caravan or indeed for anybody to, you know, criticize me or anybody else, because, you know,

00:22:07.200 --> 00:22:10.400
[Guest]: we're in the public square, we should be criticized, we should be scrutinized.

00:22:11.120 --> 00:22:17.680
[Guest]: Part of the problem I have, though, with the way this is was framed, is that, you know, a section

00:22:17.680 --> 00:22:23.760
[Guest]: of of the left is pretty similar in terms of how they view these things. It's quite similar to the

00:22:23.760 --> 00:22:28.160
[Guest]: right, I mean, except that they have, you know, better spelling and punctuation. And, you know,

00:22:28.160 --> 00:22:32.400
[Guest]: it reminds me of something that, you know, E.M. Forster once had this, you know, he divided

00:22:32.400 --> 00:22:39.520
[Guest]: characters in a novel into two types of characters, flats and rounds. And a flat character is a

00:22:39.520 --> 00:22:47.200
[Guest]: character who is essentially the same on page one, and the same on page 300. And a round character

00:22:47.200 --> 00:22:54.400
[Guest]: is a character who evolves over the arc of the novel. And I think the problem with people on

00:22:54.400 --> 00:23:01.280
[Guest]: both ends of the spectrum is that they view Modi as a flat character. Whereas I think that any

00:23:01.280 --> 00:23:08.480
[Guest]: serious politician must be viewed as a round character. It's not as though you change your

00:23:08.480 --> 00:23:15.200
[Guest]: judgment every week. It's not as though you change your judgment every month. But you are aware of

00:23:15.200 --> 00:23:22.480
[Guest]: what they are saying and doing, and your assessment changes as they evolve, right? Bill Clinton as

00:23:22.480 --> 00:23:28.480
[Guest]: governor of Arkansas is not the same as Bill Clinton as president. And I think it was, you

00:23:28.480 --> 00:23:35.040
[Guest]: could certainly, it's fair to criticize me, and it's a criticism that I accept. If you say that,

00:23:35.040 --> 00:23:43.680
[Guest]: look, you called it wrong. You thought that this guy would do certain things, and he didn't do it,

00:23:43.680 --> 00:23:47.760
[Guest]: and you were wrong. And I will accept that. And I will say, you know what, you are right.

00:23:47.760 --> 00:23:54.080
[Guest]: But I don't think it's fair to criticize someone for changing their views when the facts changed.

00:23:54.640 --> 00:23:59.680
[Amit Varma]: Right. And this is something I've, you know, I chatted about this with Ram Guha. I did a couple

00:23:59.680 --> 00:24:04.720
[Amit Varma]: of episodes on Gandhi with him. And we spoke about how people contain multitude. So it's very easy

00:24:04.720 --> 00:24:10.240
[Amit Varma]: to judge Gandhi for being A, B, or C, but people always contain multitudes. And it's similar in a

00:24:10.240 --> 00:24:16.240
[Amit Varma]: sense to Vajpayee that when, you know, he passed away, all the judgments of him was, a lot of the

00:24:16.240 --> 00:24:19.840
[Amit Varma]: judgments of him were as an essentially flat character, either he's the best Prime Minister

00:24:19.840 --> 00:24:26.320
[Amit Varma]: we had, or he's a bigoted demagogue who, you know, brought this upon us. And they're not necessarily

00:24:26.320 --> 00:24:33.040
[Amit Varma]: true. But I'm curious, when you speak of the evolution of Modi per se, would you say he really

00:24:33.040 --> 00:24:40.320
[Amit Varma]: evolved after 2014? And if so, what made him evolve? Or was it the case that the master as he

00:24:40.320 --> 00:24:48.080
[Amit Varma]: is at optics, in 2014, all he did was successfully appear all things to all people, allowing people

00:24:48.080 --> 00:24:52.560
[Amit Varma]: who wanted economic reforms to believe that he was a development guy, when actually, of course,

00:24:52.560 --> 00:24:58.720
[Amit Varma]: he wasn't. And that was him all along, or did he actually evolve? And then if he evolved away from

00:24:58.720 --> 00:25:05.520
[Amit Varma]: that development direction towards this polarizing, I nominate Sadhvi Pragya to the Lok Sabha kind of

00:25:05.520 --> 00:25:08.640
[Amit Varma]: direction, what would have brought about this evolution?

00:25:08.640 --> 00:25:13.200
[Guest]: I mean, to a certain extent, it's true that, you know, he was all things to all people. But that's

00:25:13.200 --> 00:25:18.480
[Guest]: really not unusual in politics, right? I think successful politicians are often many different

00:25:18.480 --> 00:25:23.920
[Guest]: things to many different people. So that's not something that I hold against him. I would say

00:25:23.920 --> 00:25:28.640
[Guest]: there is there was an evolution, you would say that, you know, from about 2002 to 2007,

00:25:29.440 --> 00:25:36.480
[Guest]: he was positioned and he positioned himself, really, as the Hindu strongman of Gujarat,

00:25:36.480 --> 00:25:46.080
[Guest]: right in the in the aftermath of the riots. From around 2017 to 2014. He tried to position himself

00:25:46.080 --> 00:25:51.760
[Guest]: as Mr. Development, we can get into the Gujarat model, but I don't think it was all optics,

00:25:51.760 --> 00:25:56.640
[Guest]: right? It's certainly true. And I spoke with many, many businessmen at that time, both

00:25:56.640 --> 00:26:02.480
[Guest]: foreign businessmen and domestic businessmen. And they genuinely praised they genuinely taught the

00:26:02.480 --> 00:26:07.360
[Guest]: world of him, they would tell me about how much how easy it was to do business in Gujarat,

00:26:07.360 --> 00:26:12.720
[Guest]: how well organized it was, the infrastructure, the problem solving that was centralized,

00:26:12.720 --> 00:26:20.240
[Guest]: but there was problem solving. The vibrant Gujarat summits did, did attract a fair amount

00:26:20.240 --> 00:26:25.280
[Guest]: of attention. He did say things that in hindsight, he didn't follow through on.

00:26:25.280 --> 00:26:29.360
[Guest]: But he said things like, you know, minimum government, maximum governance,

00:26:29.360 --> 00:26:34.160
[Guest]: the government has no business doing business, we're going to replace red tape with the red

00:26:34.160 --> 00:26:40.160
[Guest]: carpet. He even sort of tweeted out something when Margaret Thatcher died. So you know,

00:26:40.160 --> 00:26:44.800
[Guest]: so certainly in hindsight, it's, it's, it's fair to say that, you know, maybe some of us because

00:26:44.800 --> 00:26:54.000
[Guest]: we were, we wanted that change, so desperately, we were then willing to connect the dots in a way

00:26:54.000 --> 00:27:02.640
[Guest]: that convinced us or what we saw what we wanted to believe, and that he was clever enough to put

00:27:02.640 --> 00:27:07.040
[Guest]: some of that out there. But on the other hand, you know, you look back on that campaign, the truth

00:27:07.040 --> 00:27:14.880
[Guest]: is that it was focused on development. There was very little Hindutva in that campaign. The way he

00:27:14.880 --> 00:27:19.280
[Guest]: presented himself really was he would go into places, he would talk about jobs, he would talk

00:27:19.280 --> 00:27:24.880
[Guest]: about electricity, he would talk about inflation, he would also talk about a strong nation and

00:27:24.880 --> 00:27:32.080
[Guest]: standing up to Pakistan and China and so on. But I do think that, you know, it's one thing to

00:27:32.960 --> 00:27:39.600
[Guest]: look back in 2019. And say that, well, things did not pan out, as some of us had hoped. But

00:27:39.600 --> 00:27:46.800
[Guest]: that doesn't mean that the bet in 2014 was irrational or unjustified. The bet in 2014

00:27:46.800 --> 00:27:52.240
[Guest]: did have, there were things that were that were going for him.

00:27:52.800 --> 00:27:57.840
[Amit Varma]: Exactly. I mean, I sort of, I had an episode with Salman Sos recently, where he says the exact

00:27:57.840 --> 00:28:02.960
[Amit Varma]: same thing about 2014, that if you actually look at the BJP manifesto, he's a Congress spokesman,

00:28:02.960 --> 00:28:07.280
[Amit Varma]: but he said that he found a lot of things about the manifesto, which he liked and was hopeful that

00:28:07.280 --> 00:28:12.000
[Amit Varma]: Modi would carry those promises around. And I also had an episode a few months ago, which will be

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:16.960
[Amit Varma]: linked from the show notes with Prashant Jha, who wrote the book How the BJP Wins, where he speaks

00:28:16.960 --> 00:28:22.160
[Amit Varma]: about how Modi was a master of the narrative in terms of being able to simultaneously project

00:28:22.160 --> 00:28:29.280
[Amit Varma]: himself as one Hindu Hriday Samrat, and two, the development guy, and three, the Garibo Ka Friend

00:28:29.280 --> 00:28:35.440
[Amit Varma]: guy. And that all of these were simultaneous and working across different levels. And what you said

00:28:35.440 --> 00:28:42.800
[Amit Varma]: about how it is now obvious that, you know, that Modi didn't carry out and all of this and people

00:28:42.800 --> 00:28:49.760
[Amit Varma]: who said Modi would carry out these particular promises were wrong. And it's true that they were

00:28:49.760 --> 00:28:54.560
[Amit Varma]: wrong, but the bet wasn't necessarily wrong. And this is like, you know, I was a professional poker

00:28:54.560 --> 00:28:59.600
[Amit Varma]: player for five years, and I keep talking about the importance in everything of probabilistic

00:28:59.600 --> 00:29:05.840
[Amit Varma]: thinking. After something happens, it has either happened 100% or at 0%. But before it happens,

00:29:05.840 --> 00:29:11.680
[Amit Varma]: there are always percentages. And if you bet on something that is, say, 60% to happen,

00:29:12.480 --> 00:29:18.320
[Amit Varma]: your bet is correct. But it doesn't mean that if it doesn't happen, that, you know, you were

00:29:18.320 --> 00:29:23.280
[Amit Varma]: drastically wrong and the bet was wrong. And in that sense, even though I myself didn't support

00:29:23.280 --> 00:29:30.320
[Amit Varma]: Modi at any point, but I could understand why the support I mean, I could understand the rationale

00:29:30.320 --> 00:29:36.560
[Amit Varma]: which went behind supporting him in 2014. How did a lot of the people who supported him? How did you

00:29:36.560 --> 00:29:42.480
[Amit Varma]: in fact, then reconcile 2002 with that? Like, was it a sense of Oh, innocent until proven guilty?

00:29:42.480 --> 00:29:49.760
[Amit Varma]: And maybe he was just incompetent rather than an actual colluder in the riots? Or was it a sense

00:29:49.760 --> 00:29:56.160
[Guest]: of even if it happened, it's okay. I struggled with that a lot. And in fact, when I first started

00:29:56.160 --> 00:30:01.600
[Guest]: writing about him, and one of my first columns for the Wall Street Journal, in 2010, was titled

00:30:01.600 --> 00:30:09.680
[Guest]: Prime Minister Modi won't fly. And it was essentially about how he had done a pretty good

00:30:09.680 --> 00:30:18.240
[Guest]: job running Gujarat, how he was the most business friendly politician in India. But the taint of

00:30:18.240 --> 00:30:24.160
[Guest]: the 2002 riots essentially disqualified him from the prime ministership. And then I wrote a cover

00:30:24.160 --> 00:30:29.280
[Guest]: story for the foreign policy website, after he was reelected Chief Minister of Gujarat for the

00:30:29.280 --> 00:30:36.000
[Guest]: third time in 2012, were essentially expanded upon that same argument. So it certainly wasn't

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:41.200
[Guest]: easy for me. In the end, it was more a case of was absolutely a case of Well,

00:30:41.200 --> 00:30:50.000
[Guest]: this is a terrible episode. However, since then, there has been no further violence in Gujarat.

00:30:50.960 --> 00:30:57.360
[Guest]: Since then, he has distanced himself from and in fact, earned the enmity of the likes of Praveen

00:30:57.360 --> 00:31:01.120
[Guest]: Togadia. The VHP guys were actually campaigning against him in 2012.

00:31:01.120 --> 00:31:04.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, he kicked out Gurdansir Dadao Feo Zafaria from the cabinet.

00:31:04.240 --> 00:31:12.080
[Guest]: Dadao Feo Zafaria from the cabinet. So he had, you know, gone some distance to distance himself from

00:31:12.080 --> 00:31:20.320
[Guest]: some of these scummy elements. The SIT, what they call the clean chit did sort of also make a

00:31:20.320 --> 00:31:24.080
[Guest]: difference. You know, in the end, do you believe in rule of law? If you believe in rule of law,

00:31:24.080 --> 00:31:27.920
[Guest]: you've got to sort of, you know, this has been investigation. It was an investigation

00:31:27.920 --> 00:31:31.600
[Guest]: ordered by the Supreme Court. This was not a Gujarat government investigation.

00:31:31.600 --> 00:31:36.240
[Guest]: And so there were a lot of things which allowed you if you sort of added it all up to say that,

00:31:36.240 --> 00:31:43.280
[Guest]: well, look, this is awful. And ideally, you would not want a prime minister who

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:50.000
[Guest]: had any association with something like that. However, under the circumstances,

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:56.480
[Guest]: it comes down to him, or a third term for Congress, which has not only failed miserably

00:31:56.480 --> 00:32:01.600
[Guest]: failed miserably on the economic front, but it has also run probably the most corrupt government

00:32:01.600 --> 00:32:06.480
[Guest]: in Indian history. And what does that say about Indian democracy? If you're giving these guys

00:32:06.480 --> 00:32:11.520
[Guest]: a third term, those were the choices, they were flawed choices. And I think under those circumstances,

00:32:12.320 --> 00:32:14.000
[Guest]: to me, it was the superior choice.

00:32:14.720 --> 00:32:20.800
[Amit Varma]: In fact, as another friend of mine who supported the BJP at that time quite actively and later

00:32:20.800 --> 00:32:25.840
[Amit Varma]: changed his mind, Rajesh Jain did a long two hour episode with me on the scene and the unseen,

00:32:25.840 --> 00:32:29.440
[Amit Varma]: which I recommend everyone listen to, that will be in the show notes. And the way he put it was

00:32:29.440 --> 00:32:34.320
[Amit Varma]: he supported them because they were the lighter shade of grey. And I mean, with hindsight, of

00:32:34.320 --> 00:32:38.080
[Amit Varma]: course, you can look back and say, hey, no way. But you know, at the time, I think that's reasonable

00:32:38.080 --> 00:32:41.680
[Amit Varma]: enough. So tell me, you know, looking back through, say, the last five years, before we get

00:32:41.680 --> 00:32:45.840
[Amit Varma]: to these elections, looking back through the last five years, at around what point did you begin to

00:32:45.840 --> 00:32:52.480
[Amit Varma]: feel that, wait a minute, you know, this guy is not going to do any of the development stuff.

00:32:52.480 --> 00:32:57.360
[Amit Varma]: Instead, you know, there are lynchings happening. And all of this is so you know,

00:32:57.360 --> 00:33:03.840
[Guest]: I was hopeful, obviously, when he came into office, my journal column, the week he was elected,

00:33:03.840 --> 00:33:08.560
[Guest]: was essentially said India votes for hope, which I believe was definitely the case,

00:33:08.560 --> 00:33:15.120
[Guest]: which is, I mean, true, regardless of how it turned out. Exactly. Now, I became critical right

00:33:15.120 --> 00:33:20.160
[Guest]: away. I criticized the first budget because it was the interim budget, because it was just,

00:33:20.160 --> 00:33:25.920
[Guest]: there was such a huge opportunity, right? Get rid of this retroactive tax. There was so much

00:33:25.920 --> 00:33:32.880
[Guest]: he could have done to just dominate the headlines in the financial press. And they dropped the ball

00:33:32.880 --> 00:33:40.160
[Guest]: right away. So I was critical right away. And in terms of the interim budget in terms of the first

00:33:40.160 --> 00:33:45.920
[Guest]: budget, because already, you could sort of see that they were not doing many of the things that

00:33:45.920 --> 00:33:52.320
[Guest]: I had hoped that they would do. Similarly, I was critical right away, when Akhlaq happened. And

00:33:52.320 --> 00:33:59.680
[Guest]: again, that was frankly, such a gimme. All he had to do was step up and say the right thing.

00:33:59.680 --> 00:34:05.280
[Guest]: It was the easiest thing to do in the world. This is a guy whose own brother was in the Air Force,

00:34:05.280 --> 00:34:10.640
[Guest]: right? I mean, all basic humanity just demanded that you say something, embrace the family,

00:34:10.640 --> 00:34:17.120
[Guest]: and he dropped the ball. But those criticisms were episodic. So it was like, well, you have not done

00:34:17.120 --> 00:34:22.960
[Guest]: this, and you ought to do it. For me, there were two things that really began to fundamentally

00:34:22.960 --> 00:34:28.720
[Guest]: change how I viewed this government. And on the economic front, it was demonetization,

00:34:29.280 --> 00:34:34.560
[Guest]: which is, of course, no surprise. And it's the case for many people. Demonetization,

00:34:34.560 --> 00:34:43.760
[Guest]: the just the sheer stupidity of it, the sheer callousness of it, the opacity of the decision

00:34:43.760 --> 00:34:49.920
[Guest]: making, I mean, at every level, right? This is really, you know, I use, I describe demonetization

00:34:49.920 --> 00:34:57.360
[Unknown]: as too crazy for Venezuela. They consider it and said, No, wait a minute, if you've got a policy

00:34:57.360 --> 00:35:03.600
[Guest]: that's too crazy for Venezuela, you're in trouble. So on the economic front, it was really, it was

00:35:03.600 --> 00:35:10.640
[Guest]: demonetization that, you know, was the straw that broke the camel's back. And on the cultural side,

00:35:10.640 --> 00:35:15.920
[Guest]: it was the appointment of Yogi Adityanath. Because at some point, you just have to say,

00:35:16.960 --> 00:35:24.160
[Guest]: look, where is this train headed? And the way where this train is headed is not where I want

00:35:24.160 --> 00:35:30.480
[Guest]: to go. So I have to get off. And I remember having conversations with many of my friends who were

00:35:30.480 --> 00:35:34.960
[Guest]: very close to the government, and in fact, remain close to the government. And and I said, look,

00:35:35.520 --> 00:35:41.120
[Guest]: where are the brakes on this thing? And I never got a satisfactory answer. And I still don't have

00:35:41.120 --> 00:35:46.800
[Amit Varma]: a satisfactory answer. Yeah, in fact, I mean, I was equally aghast by demon, I was writing about

00:35:46.800 --> 00:35:50.800
[Amit Varma]: it from the week it came out, I've had multiple episodes on it, it is essentially the largest

00:35:50.800 --> 00:35:55.520
[Amit Varma]: assault on property rights in human history, as I see it. You know, I compared Modi to Mao at that

00:35:55.520 --> 00:36:00.880
[Amit Varma]: time, in fact, in the Times of India, and got a lot of flack for that. But you know, going back

00:36:00.880 --> 00:36:05.440
[Amit Varma]: to what you said earlier about say, Akhlaq's killing, and at that point, Modi could so easily

00:36:05.440 --> 00:36:09.840
[Amit Varma]: have just put out a two sentence statement, and that would have kind of covered his ass, but he

00:36:09.840 --> 00:36:15.120
[Amit Varma]: didn't even do that. He stayed silent. And what we've seen is that all through most of this period,

00:36:15.120 --> 00:36:19.120
[Amit Varma]: the cow lynchings and the stuff that's been happening. I mean, he's occasionally come out

00:36:19.120 --> 00:36:24.400
[Amit Varma]: and said a couple of things, but mostly he's been silent. What do you think the incentives on him

00:36:24.400 --> 00:36:32.560
[Amit Varma]: are? Like, how much of the control does the RSS have on the BJP and Modi? How much is Modi himself

00:36:32.560 --> 00:36:37.840
[Amit Varma]: a true believer in Hindutva? Because with you know, with every politician, there's always sort

00:36:37.840 --> 00:36:43.040
[Amit Varma]: of a trade off between what you really believe in, and your will to power, what you know, kind

00:36:43.040 --> 00:36:47.920
[Amit Varma]: of gets you there in the first place. And my sort of take of Modi once upon a time was that look,

00:36:47.920 --> 00:36:51.600
[Amit Varma]: he's a sociopath, he'll do anything to come to power, he doesn't necessarily have any beliefs

00:36:51.600 --> 00:36:57.280
[Amit Varma]: of his own. He'll just do whatever gets him in power. And yet, through all this point, you know,

00:36:57.280 --> 00:37:02.240
[Amit Varma]: if he stays silent through all of this, if he nominates Pragya Thakur as an MP, as he did

00:37:02.240 --> 00:37:07.760
[Amit Varma]: recently, then you've really got to wonder that either the pressures on him from the RSS are huge,

00:37:07.760 --> 00:37:13.840
[Guest]: or he's actually a Hindutva believer. You know, I don't have a good answer to that. And in a way,

00:37:13.840 --> 00:37:19.280
[Guest]: it almost doesn't matter. I actually don't really care what Modi thinks at three in the morning.

00:37:19.280 --> 00:37:25.040
[Guest]: Yeah, it's irrelevant. I judge him by what he says, and what he does as Prime Minister.

00:37:25.760 --> 00:37:32.800
[Guest]: And whether at three in the morning, tossing in his bed, he is actually appalled by his own silence,

00:37:32.800 --> 00:37:39.440
[Guest]: or whether he is secretly exultant, is kind of irrelevant. That was just, you know,

00:37:39.440 --> 00:37:46.320
[Guest]: that moment stood out for me, partly because of, you know, the story there, the family story over

00:37:46.320 --> 00:37:53.600
[Guest]: there. The simplest thing to do would be to put out a statement, and then frankly, to invite the

00:37:53.600 --> 00:37:59.280
[Guest]: brother who was a mechanic in the Air Force, invite him to the Prime Minister's residence,

00:37:59.280 --> 00:38:04.480
[Guest]: and just reach out and show that you don't put religion above humanity. You don't put,

00:38:04.480 --> 00:38:10.320
[Guest]: you know, religious sentiments above basic humanity. So he dropped the ball on that. The

00:38:10.320 --> 00:38:16.960
[Guest]: way it's been explained to me is that, you know, there is a certain percentage of this population,

00:38:16.960 --> 00:38:24.000
[Guest]: I mean, this classic base politics, you have a certain amount of the base, which would be upset

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:30.560
[Guest]: if he'd done that. And he wasn't willing to take on that. I mean, what's interesting is that

00:38:31.680 --> 00:38:36.800
[Guest]: if you look at Modi's own statements over these last five years, not counting some of the stuff

00:38:36.800 --> 00:38:43.600
[Guest]: he said in the campaign, by and large, he said the sort of things that world leaders say,

00:38:44.160 --> 00:38:50.720
[Guest]: he's gone and addressed conferences and said that Islam is a religion of peace, he's sort of,

00:38:50.720 --> 00:38:56.160
[Guest]: you know, made the right noises when he goes to the Middle East, and so on, and Abu Dhabi and

00:38:56.160 --> 00:39:00.960
[Guest]: places like that. So it's not as though most of his rhetoric, not counting the campaign,

00:39:00.960 --> 00:39:07.440
[Guest]: and we can get to that, most of his own rhetoric has been reasonable as Prime Minister.

00:39:08.960 --> 00:39:15.760
[Guest]: The problem arises in his first of all, the silences, and those silences cannot be wished

00:39:15.760 --> 00:39:23.920
[Guest]: away. And secondly, in the kinds of people he has empowered. And as long as if you really wanted to

00:39:23.920 --> 00:39:31.200
[Guest]: give him the benefit of the doubt, which I did, as long as you had, you know, the likes of Yogi

00:39:31.200 --> 00:39:38.640
[Guest]: Adityanath and Giriraj Singh and some of these other people, as part of the coalition, but very

00:39:38.640 --> 00:39:46.000
[Guest]: clearly kept at a distance and not people in power. That was something that I was willing to live

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:50.800
[Guest]: with, right? I mean, you have, this is true of conservative movements everywhere that you're

00:39:50.800 --> 00:39:57.760
[Guest]: going to have some people who are not very responsible, not very likable. But as long as

00:39:57.760 --> 00:40:05.520
[Guest]: the responsible elements are in charge, you live with that. The problem arises when you start

00:40:05.520 --> 00:40:12.000
[Guest]: mainstreaming those people, right? And when you take someone whose main claim to fame is his

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:17.520
[Guest]: violent, inflammatory, anti-Muslim rhetoric, and you put him in charge of India's largest state,

00:40:17.520 --> 00:40:21.520
[Guest]: what are you saying? What's the signal you're sending to the next generation of BJP leaders?

00:40:22.800 --> 00:40:29.360
[Guest]: You're saying that this is the fast track to a brilliant political career. You do this,

00:40:29.360 --> 00:40:32.720
[Guest]: and you get to be the second youngest chief minister in the history of Uttar Pradesh.

00:40:33.760 --> 00:40:37.600
[Guest]: And so there was just absolutely no way to explain that. And I still look back on these

00:40:37.600 --> 00:40:44.160
[Guest]: five years, and I think that he could have just done a few things differently. Because if you

00:40:44.160 --> 00:40:50.640
[Guest]: look at most of his chief ministerial picks, they're pretty centrist figures from within the

00:40:50.640 --> 00:40:55.840
[Guest]: BJP. If you look at most of his senior ministers, these are people who choose their words carefully.

00:40:56.480 --> 00:41:01.840
[Guest]: Sushma Swaraj, Rajnath Singh, Gadkari, Jaitley, these are not people who are shooting their mouth

00:41:01.840 --> 00:41:06.880
[Guest]: off and talking about, you know, if you kill one of mine, I'll kill 100 of yours or standing,

00:41:06.880 --> 00:41:11.120
[Guest]: sitting on stage while someone is talking about digging up corpses. I mean, they don't,

00:41:11.120 --> 00:41:17.360
[Guest]: they're just they're very far away from that. And I think that this is where Modi's BJP

00:41:18.160 --> 00:41:19.280
[Guest]: really lost the plot.

00:41:20.320 --> 00:41:25.600
[Amit Varma]: And I think, you know, for me, in fact, Adityanath being made chief minister was

00:41:26.480 --> 00:41:33.360
[Amit Varma]: also a sort of a very revelatory moment. I wrote a column at the time arguing that this was

00:41:33.360 --> 00:41:38.640
[Amit Varma]: sort of society striking back at the elite. So let me ask you a question. I've asked Shashi

00:41:38.640 --> 00:41:43.440
[Amit Varma]: Tharoor on the show, I asked Aakar Patel, we did a long episode on Hindutva. And I'll come back to

00:41:43.440 --> 00:41:48.240
[Amit Varma]: that later. And I asked him as well. And it's something that still bothers me, which is this,

00:41:48.240 --> 00:41:53.760
[Amit Varma]: that our elites drafted a liberal constitution, not liberal enough for me in terms of protecting

00:41:53.760 --> 00:41:59.280
[Amit Varma]: individual rights, but by and large, liberal. Our elites drafted a liberal constitution,

00:41:59.840 --> 00:42:06.000
[Amit Varma]: and imposed it top down upon a country that you could argue was really an illiberal society.

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:14.320
[Amit Varma]: And the question then arises, that how is that imposition of a liberal constitution

00:42:14.320 --> 00:42:20.720
[Amit Varma]: on an illiberal society? Is that itself not an illiberal act? And if society then decides to

00:42:20.720 --> 00:42:26.160
[Amit Varma]: strike back and say that no, we are illiberal, we like our illiberalism to hell with what you

00:42:26.160 --> 00:42:31.840
[Amit Varma]: elites try to impose on us? How are we to sort of answer that? And this, by the way, was a point that,

00:42:31.840 --> 00:42:36.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, even in different language, and I found out later after I'd made it, a point that even

00:42:36.480 --> 00:42:41.760
[Amit Varma]: Dindayal Upadhyay, who is one of Modi's heroes, had himself made in his time?

00:42:41.760 --> 00:42:47.040
[Guest]: Yeah, I think it's a tough question. Because the people who have drafted the constitution

00:42:47.040 --> 00:42:52.640
[Guest]: were not remotely representative of India. Right? If you just sort of look at their profiles,

00:42:52.640 --> 00:43:00.640
[Guest]: look at their level of education, look at their, look at their wealth, look at their exposure to

00:43:00.640 --> 00:43:06.560
[Guest]: Western learning, start with Ambedkar with his PhD from Columbia, this was clearly

00:43:06.560 --> 00:43:13.120
[Guest]: unrepresentative of India. And that perhaps if you'd had a referendum in the aftermath of

00:43:13.760 --> 00:43:20.640
[Guest]: partition, and of what kind of state you wanted to be, maybe the majority would indeed have voted

00:43:20.640 --> 00:43:25.840
[Guest]: for some kind of Hindu Rashtra. And so I think that's a fair point. But I think at the same time,

00:43:25.840 --> 00:43:30.000
[Guest]: if you happen to believe in certain ideas, because you think that those are the superior

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:36.160
[Guest]: ideas, and they are, they offer you a better way of ordering society and ordering government,

00:43:37.520 --> 00:43:41.360
[Guest]: then you'd still stand by it, because it's a value judgment, you think that

00:43:41.360 --> 00:43:45.600
[Guest]: those liberal ideas are better ideas, and they're worth fighting for.

00:43:46.480 --> 00:43:51.600
[Amit Varma]: I mean, my position on that simply is that if we want a liberal society, then we get to that

00:43:51.600 --> 00:43:55.920
[Amit Varma]: liberal society through the culture, we change the culture, it has to happen bottoms up,

00:43:55.920 --> 00:44:01.440
[Amit Varma]: it can't happen top down. And in a sense, the fact that Adityanath is the chief minister,

00:44:01.440 --> 00:44:07.680
[Amit Varma]: that Pragya Singh Thakur is an MP, that Modi won such a big election just now, is a testament of

00:44:07.680 --> 00:44:11.680
[Amit Varma]: the failure of the top down approach, you can't impose liberal values, you have to

00:44:11.680 --> 00:44:16.880
[Amit Varma]: seed them into the culture. And that is a task at which liberals in India have failed utterly,

00:44:16.880 --> 00:44:18.640
[Amit Varma]: however one defines the word liberals.

00:44:18.640 --> 00:44:22.800
[Guest]: Well, it depends, right? I mean, if you look around the region, I still think that

00:44:23.760 --> 00:44:27.440
[Guest]: in some ways, India has been more successful than any other country in the region.

00:44:28.560 --> 00:44:35.200
[Guest]: I think that the Indian elites, I think the collision of the Indian elites with Western

00:44:35.200 --> 00:44:41.360
[Guest]: ideas, you know, the whole Macaulay project, it's run much deeper in India than, for example,

00:44:41.360 --> 00:44:48.800
[Guest]: in Pakistan, certainly. And so there's no equivalent of, say, the times of India in any

00:44:48.800 --> 00:44:53.440
[Guest]: other country in this region. So I think that there was a moment if we'd been having this

00:44:53.440 --> 00:45:00.320
[Guest]: conversation in, say, 1974, you could have said that things are going to go turn out in a

00:45:00.320 --> 00:45:06.640
[Guest]: different way, right? In fact, even if we'd been having this conversation in 2010, it looked like

00:45:06.640 --> 00:45:11.920
[Guest]: the BJP would never be a serious contender for power. And that though India was not a

00:45:11.920 --> 00:45:17.600
[Guest]: perfectly liberal society, it was certainly liberal in many ways. And in the direction

00:45:17.600 --> 00:45:23.920
[Guest]: in which it was moving, was towards, you know, more individual rights, more freedom of speech,

00:45:23.920 --> 00:45:24.960
[Guest]: and so on.

00:45:24.960 --> 00:45:28.720
[Amit Varma]: Driven as much perhaps by globalization and technology and all of those things.

00:45:28.720 --> 00:45:32.960
[Guest]: So that was a real moment, right? And I think in many ways, this is sort of this is where

00:45:32.960 --> 00:45:36.960
[Guest]: what's happening here fits into what's happening in so many other parts of the world.

00:45:36.960 --> 00:45:43.040
[Guest]: Because, you know, in that end of history moment, right, Berlin Wall falls, and then

00:45:43.040 --> 00:45:48.000
[Guest]: you have Indian liberalization kicking off in two years later in 1991, there was a certain

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:53.120
[Guest]: self confidence among global elites. And that was certainly something that was reflected

00:45:53.120 --> 00:45:58.240
[Guest]: in India, where there was, you know, one kind of narrative that was dominant. I don't think

00:45:58.240 --> 00:46:04.720
[Guest]: it's died entirely. But obviously, you know, liberalism is severely on the back foot right

00:46:04.720 --> 00:46:05.280
[Guest]: now.

00:46:05.280 --> 00:46:11.680
[Amit Varma]: And to sort of, you know, go back to Hindutva, again, I had an episode with Aakar on the

00:46:11.680 --> 00:46:17.680
[Amit Varma]: intellectual traditions that drive the RSS and the BJP and so on. And there are two ways

00:46:17.680 --> 00:46:22.720
[Amit Varma]: to look at the BJP. Obviously, one is that it's a modernizing party, in a sense, as under

00:46:22.720 --> 00:46:30.480
[Amit Varma]: watched by it right to be. But the other is also that it is carrying a long old tradition,

00:46:30.480 --> 00:46:34.240
[Amit Varma]: actually not very old, but I mean, old in the sense of, you know, maybe 100 years old,

00:46:34.240 --> 00:46:40.160
[Amit Varma]: but not old in a deeper civilizational sense. But it's carrying that tradition forward.

00:46:40.160 --> 00:46:46.080
[Amit Varma]: And this is sort of what it all comes down to. So now, you know, for example, you work

00:46:46.080 --> 00:46:51.040
[Amit Varma]: in a think tank, which is considered a conservative think tank. And you've obviously thought about

00:46:51.040 --> 00:46:57.600
[Amit Varma]: conservatism a fair deal. And I'd argue there's no analog of Burkean conservatism per se in

00:46:57.600 --> 00:47:05.280
[Amit Varma]: India. But the BJP does represent a certain kind of conservatism. And to you, what are

00:47:05.280 --> 00:47:10.080
[Amit Varma]: the intellectual traditions really driving the BJP? Are there any coherent traditions?

00:47:10.080 --> 00:47:13.520
[Amit Varma]: Or is it just driven by bigotry and the sense of the other?

00:47:13.520 --> 00:47:17.200
[Guest]: I mean, I guess in some ways you could, I mean, I haven't really pondered this, but

00:47:17.200 --> 00:47:22.960
[Guest]: you could argue that the traditionalist view that was reflected in some of the Johnson's

00:47:22.960 --> 00:47:29.680
[Guest]: thought, for example, don't move too fast to amend Hindu personal laws. I mean, you

00:47:29.680 --> 00:47:34.560
[Guest]: could argue in a sense that that's Burkean, don't go too fast, you know, let these things

00:47:34.560 --> 00:47:39.840
[Guest]: are organic, let them proceed at their own pace, and so on. But I think your larger point

00:47:39.840 --> 00:47:47.200
[Guest]: is true, because the the BJP is fundamentally revolutionary. And they're not interested

00:47:47.200 --> 00:47:53.760
[Guest]: in conserving in the in the Burkean sense, as much as they are in appending what they

00:47:53.760 --> 00:47:59.920
[Guest]: think has gone, what has gone wrong in this, in this society. Now, again, you can sort

00:47:59.920 --> 00:48:06.800
[Guest]: of go back to, you know, Savarkar and Golwalkar and Dindayal Upadhyay, right? And he gave those

00:48:06.800 --> 00:48:13.360
[Guest]: four famous lectures on integral humanism and, and see this quest to, you know, reimagine

00:48:13.360 --> 00:48:21.040
[Guest]: the world through this pious Hindu lens. And, you know, in some ways, I think, you know,

00:48:21.040 --> 00:48:26.320
[Guest]: the closest analog, because I've spent some time traveling with and talking to and reading

00:48:26.320 --> 00:48:32.280
[Guest]: about Islamists is, you know, that's where the parallels are very interesting, right?

00:48:32.280 --> 00:48:40.360
[Guest]: There was this need for a mythical golden age, you sort of have to root your present

00:48:40.360 --> 00:48:46.400
[Guest]: in the idea of past greatness, right? And for the Islamists, this is the era of the

00:48:46.400 --> 00:48:54.160
[Guest]: first four caliphs. And for the Hindutva guys, it's ancient pre Islamic India. So there's

00:48:54.160 --> 00:49:01.880
[Guest]: that commonality, there's the idea that your faith is better than everybody else's, right?

00:49:01.880 --> 00:49:07.400
[Guest]: So if you ever point out, for instance, that secularism is under threat, immediately 100

00:49:07.400 --> 00:49:12.600
[Guest]: people on Twitter will tell you it is not possible, because we are just innately tolerant,

00:49:12.600 --> 00:49:17.920
[Guest]: we have the best, most innately tolerant faith imaginable. And if you don't agree, we'll

00:49:17.920 --> 00:49:23.960
[Guest]: troll you. So you get that. And again, it's very similar to sort of, you know, how Islamists

00:49:23.960 --> 00:49:29.960
[Guest]: view sort of the faith is kind of this, you know, Judaism and Christianity are just like,

00:49:29.960 --> 00:49:36.120
[Guest]: we're trying stuff out. And then he finally got it right with Islam. So there is that

00:49:36.120 --> 00:49:42.280
[Guest]: the difference lies, I think, and it's an important difference, in that the Islamists

00:49:42.280 --> 00:49:49.180
[Guest]: are much more programmatic. And part of this is because they have relatively recent history

00:49:49.180 --> 00:49:55.160
[Guest]: to fall back on, in terms of how society in the state was organized, right? The caliphate

00:49:55.160 --> 00:50:00.640
[Guest]: was only abolished in 1924. So they can sort of go back and think, you know, and say that,

00:50:00.640 --> 00:50:05.800
[Guest]: well, look, this is how we used to do things, not that long ago. And so what they have is

00:50:05.800 --> 00:50:10.680
[Guest]: much more prescriptive in terms of policy. So when I was in Indonesia, and I was traveling

00:50:10.680 --> 00:50:14.560
[Guest]: with Islamists, you know, you could ask them all kinds of questions, right? What should

00:50:14.560 --> 00:50:18.480
[Guest]: the currency look like? And they said, well, you know, we should have the gold dinar and

00:50:18.480 --> 00:50:23.040
[Guest]: the silver dirham. If we did that, then the price of the chicken today would be the same

00:50:23.040 --> 00:50:27.720
[Guest]: as it was 1000 years ago. And what should movie theaters look like? Well, there shouldn't

00:50:27.720 --> 00:50:30.840
[Guest]: be movie theaters, but there's some ones who wanted movie theaters. Well, okay, the women

00:50:30.840 --> 00:50:35.280
[Guest]: should sit in one place, and the men should sit in one place. What should a banking system

00:50:35.280 --> 00:50:40.040
[Guest]: look like? Well, there should be no interest rate. So they have a lot of this stuff that's

00:50:40.040 --> 00:50:46.120
[Guest]: worked out. Whereas with the Hindutva folks, in some ways, you could argue it makes them

00:50:46.120 --> 00:50:52.800
[Guest]: more benign, because they don't really have much of a program. They might get there, but

00:50:52.800 --> 00:50:57.040
[Guest]: they don't have that. They haven't sort of thought about these things in the same way.

00:50:57.040 --> 00:51:03.000
[Guest]: But in other ways, it's scary, because what they do have these sort of inchoate sense

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:07.960
[Guest]: of resentments. And you can't really beyond a point have a rational conversation with

00:51:07.960 --> 00:51:14.400
[Guest]: many of them, because at some level, their conception of time is a pre modern conception

00:51:14.400 --> 00:51:20.440
[Guest]: of time. And I'm always struck by this in, you know, TV studio debate with a BJP guy,

00:51:20.440 --> 00:51:26.640
[Guest]: and he'd be talking about something that happened in, you know, 1525, as though it happened

00:51:26.640 --> 00:51:30.920
[Guest]: last Tuesday, right? There's no capacity to sort of say that, well, you know, this just

00:51:30.920 --> 00:51:36.200
[Guest]: this happened to me on my way to the studio. And this is something that happened 500 years

00:51:36.200 --> 00:51:42.520
[Guest]: ago. And we don't normally, these things don't exist on the same plane in our minds. But

00:51:42.520 --> 00:51:50.480
[Guest]: for these guys, for many of them, they do. So it's very difficult to, you know, to have

00:51:50.480 --> 00:51:57.600
[Guest]: a fair, rational, reasoned conversation, when someone first of all, their starting point

00:51:57.600 --> 00:52:02.240
[Guest]: is that they must settle the scores of history. Right? I can have a conversation, we can have

00:52:02.240 --> 00:52:07.840
[Guest]: a disagreement, and I can sort of you and I can come to a compromise. But if I've decided

00:52:07.840 --> 00:52:14.280
[Guest]: that you are responsible for something your ancestors may or may not have done 500 years

00:52:14.280 --> 00:52:21.800
[Guest]: ago, what can you do? What can you do to satisfy me? That is one problem. And then the other

00:52:21.800 --> 00:52:29.440
[Guest]: problem, which is again, quite similar to the Islamists is just the inability to speak

00:52:29.440 --> 00:52:35.600
[Guest]: rationally or reasonably about certain kinds of things. So I was on an NDTV debate last

00:52:35.600 --> 00:52:42.920
[Guest]: week. And one of these guys, sort of BJP oriented guys started talking about Hindu terror and

00:52:42.920 --> 00:52:46.960
[Guest]: how this was this horrible thing. And how can you talk about Hindu terror and you're

00:52:46.960 --> 00:52:52.280
[Guest]: defaming a billion people. And to me, that was just like, it's a completely absurd argument,

00:52:52.280 --> 00:52:58.560
[Guest]: right? Now, if I describe somebody as an Italian mafia don, it doesn't mean that all Italians

00:52:58.560 --> 00:53:03.640
[Guest]: are mafia dons. I've just said that this person is an Italian mafia don. And you can be a

00:53:03.640 --> 00:53:07.800
[Unknown]: terrorist from any group, you can be a Tamil terrorist, you can be a Basque terrorist,

00:53:07.800 --> 00:53:13.040
[Unknown]: you can be a Mormon terrorist. Is it true you can be an Islamic terrorist? Is it true

00:53:13.040 --> 00:53:22.480
[Unknown]: that there are relatively few Hindu terrorists? Yes, I'll grant you that. Like very relatively

00:53:22.480 --> 00:53:28.680
[Guest]: few cases where people inspired by the faith or their sense of defending the faith have

00:53:28.680 --> 00:53:36.520
[Guest]: gone out and murdered or attempted to murder random civilians. Fair enough. But you can't

00:53:36.520 --> 00:53:41.480
[Guest]: say that this is simply not possible because you have some kind of mathematical equation

00:53:41.480 --> 00:53:47.720
[Guest]: in your head that says that a Hindu can never be a terrorist. And I feel that on these kinds

00:53:47.720 --> 00:53:55.680
[Guest]: of questions, the space to even speak, I mean, this is not rocket science, right? This is

00:53:55.680 --> 00:54:01.880
[Guest]: something so it's basic, it's commonsensical. It's just how you use language. But I've had

00:54:01.880 --> 00:54:07.760
[Guest]: these conversations with people who are, who I regard as intelligent people, and who you

00:54:07.760 --> 00:54:13.640
[Guest]: could have a reasonable conversation with about many, many other topics. But when it

00:54:13.640 --> 00:54:17.840
[Guest]: comes to this, they're not able to discuss it rationally. And so I think that's another

00:54:17.840 --> 00:54:23.200
[Guest]: sort of, you know, it's a similarity, right? Because you can't have a reasonable conversation

00:54:23.200 --> 00:54:30.880
[Guest]: about the blasphemy law in Pakistan. You know, this is and I fear that we are, you know,

00:54:30.880 --> 00:54:35.760
[Guest]: increasingly in similar territory on some of these things, because if you mention something,

00:54:35.760 --> 00:54:42.680
[Guest]: it'll immediately be bent out of shape, it'll be distorted. And they essentially the way

00:54:42.680 --> 00:54:47.160
[Guest]: they operate is that then they said a mob on you to sort of claim that you said something

00:54:47.160 --> 00:54:53.400
[Guest]: that you didn't say. And it's an effective strategy. I mean, unfortunately, right. And,

00:54:53.400 --> 00:54:57.120
[Amit Varma]: you know, one question I've asked others, such as our car and that I wonder about is

00:54:57.120 --> 00:55:02.080
[Amit Varma]: that, where do these resentments, this anger, this bitterness, where do they all come from?

00:55:02.080 --> 00:55:06.400
[Amit Varma]: Because if you actually look at Hindus in India, they're far better off than Muslims.

00:55:06.400 --> 00:55:10.960
[Amit Varma]: In your everyday life, you're not being victimized by them or dominated by them or so on. You

00:55:10.960 --> 00:55:16.160
[Amit Varma]: know, even Hitler, you know, the resentment that he had against the Jews could be explained

00:55:16.160 --> 00:55:22.280
[Amit Varma]: because the Jews were dominant in terms of finance or whatever. And you, you know, but

00:55:22.280 --> 00:55:27.920
[Amit Varma]: Muslims are literally the downtrodden of India, they're far poorer in general than Hindus

00:55:27.920 --> 00:55:34.840
[Amit Varma]: are definitely far worse off. Why are these resentments so widespread, that so many common

00:55:34.840 --> 00:55:39.040
[Amit Varma]: people feel resentful towards the other, so to say,

00:55:39.040 --> 00:55:45.760
[Guest]: a couple of reasons. First of all, I think once you start feeling like a victim, then

00:55:45.760 --> 00:55:49.840
[Guest]: you can always look for signs of your own victimhood. I agree with you that this sort

00:55:49.840 --> 00:55:53.120
[Guest]: of doesn't measure up to the facts. But when I talk to people who do believe this, here

00:55:53.120 --> 00:55:58.720
[Guest]: are the kinds of things that they say. They would look, first of all, the important history

00:55:58.720 --> 00:56:04.800
[Guest]: is very, very important, right? So someone like Rajiv Malhotra would say that, look,

00:56:04.800 --> 00:56:10.560
[Guest]: 1000 years ago, before the advent of Islam and the subcontinent, there were Indonesia

00:56:10.560 --> 00:56:17.960
[Guest]: was a Hindu, Java was a Hindu island, Sumatra was Hindu, Hinduism sort of stretched across

00:56:17.960 --> 00:56:27.000
[Guest]: Afghanistan, was Buddhist and so on. And then the physical space for Indic religions has

00:56:27.000 --> 00:56:35.040
[Guest]: been shrinking because it's been under assault from Abrahamic religions, primarily Islam.

00:56:35.040 --> 00:56:40.280
[Guest]: Then they would look, for example, at something like Kashmir and, you know, terrible tragedy

00:56:40.280 --> 00:56:46.680
[Guest]: of the Kashmiri pundits driven out and that would sort of be another, another data point.

00:56:46.680 --> 00:56:51.240
[Guest]: Then they would look obviously at partition and the bloodshed of partition, the ethnic

00:56:51.240 --> 00:56:57.080
[Guest]: cleansing that accompanied partition and again, sort of see that, look, the Hindus were at

00:56:57.080 --> 00:57:02.080
[Guest]: the receiving end of this. And then they look at provisions in the constitution and they

00:57:02.080 --> 00:57:08.720
[Guest]: look at the idea of minority rights, the way it was framed in India, not as protections,

00:57:08.720 --> 00:57:14.760
[Guest]: which was the idea, but as special rights. And there's a certain element of truth to

00:57:14.760 --> 00:57:18.840
[Guest]: that, right. So you know, I think one of the telling examples, I think this is where the

00:57:18.840 --> 00:57:25.200
[Guest]: sort of the Hindutva approach to some of these issues deviates from the classical liberal

00:57:25.200 --> 00:57:31.200
[Guest]: approach is the RTE. And the RTE is, you know, as you've written and others have written

00:57:31.200 --> 00:57:37.040
[Guest]: it, it's a, it's a terrible piece of legislation. It's the worst of Indian statism. It's intrusive

00:57:37.040 --> 00:57:41.280
[Guest]: and it's placing all these rules and restrictions and it's, you know, focused more on inputs

00:57:41.280 --> 00:57:49.000
[Guest]: and on outcomes. Now, you and I, when we look at RTE, the way we think about it is that,

00:57:49.000 --> 00:57:54.920
[Guest]: well, get the state out of this. And so we should liberate. So obviously, you know, religious

00:57:54.920 --> 00:57:59.560
[Guest]: schools like Christian and Muslim schools are not, are exempt, they're minority exemptions.

00:57:59.560 --> 00:58:04.240
[Guest]: And so our way of looking at that would be, well, let's exempt everybody. Everyone can

00:58:04.240 --> 00:58:10.520
[Guest]: be equal and everybody can be, you take the hand of government off. The way they see the

00:58:10.520 --> 00:58:17.400
[Guest]: same thing, they see the differential. But what they want is for everybody to be controlled.

00:58:17.400 --> 00:58:21.720
[Guest]: Can we get the government to regulate their schools too? So it's not as though they don't

00:58:21.720 --> 00:58:34.160
[Guest]: have a story. But what you need to do is then make the leap into this idea of constant persecution,

00:58:34.160 --> 00:58:40.040
[Guest]: which, which simply doesn't exist. There is no persecution, right? I mean, I blame the

00:58:40.040 --> 00:58:43.920
[Guest]: liberals for some of their missteps. I blame, you know, Manmohan Singh for making that,

00:58:43.920 --> 00:58:48.680
[Guest]: you know, statement about, you know, Muslims have the first right of resources. That was

00:58:48.680 --> 00:58:53.320
[Guest]: not something that a leader of a secular state should say. He should really have said everybody

00:58:53.320 --> 00:58:58.040
[Guest]: has equal resources. But the fact is that in the end, the people who really got the

00:58:58.040 --> 00:59:02.120
[Guest]: short end of the stick over there were Indian Muslims. It's not as though he actually went

00:59:02.120 --> 00:59:07.840
[Guest]: and, you know, actually got the first dibs on resources. He just said something stupid.

00:59:07.840 --> 00:59:14.440
[Guest]: That stupid thing that he said fed resentment. Muslims never had anything to do with that.

00:59:14.440 --> 00:59:20.300
[Guest]: He said it. And, but these, I think in many ways, the sort of traditional left of center

00:59:20.300 --> 00:59:26.000
[Guest]: Indian parties have, they've played some of this stuff really badly. And I think that

00:59:26.000 --> 00:59:31.960
[Guest]: from the 80s onwards, they've really misunderstood the nature of Islamism, the changing patterns

00:59:31.960 --> 00:59:38.080
[Guest]: in the world and so on. And what that allowed the Sangh Parivar to do was to couch many

00:59:38.080 --> 00:59:44.920
[Guest]: of their arguments in, you know, classical liberal terms or in terms of, in terms of

00:59:44.920 --> 00:59:51.560
[Guest]: just fairness. For example, I agree that there should be a uniform civil code. I agree that

00:59:51.560 --> 00:59:57.880
[Guest]: the Indian taxpayer should not subsidize the Hajj subsidy. But the difference is that when

00:59:57.880 --> 01:00:02.000
[Guest]: the Hajj subsidy was abolished, I was, you know, I was, I was happy. And then I made

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:08.560
[Guest]: the point on Twitter that you should also abolish this Mansarovar subsidy, right? It's

01:00:08.560 --> 01:00:13.760
[Guest]: exactly the same principle. Why should the state be paying for someone's pilgrimage?

01:00:13.760 --> 01:00:17.120
[Guest]: You could do your pilgrimage on your own money. Why should the taxpayer pay? And it doesn't

01:00:17.120 --> 01:00:21.480
[Guest]: matter whether you're Muslim, Hindu, Christian. The problem is that when you, so they're very

01:00:21.480 --> 01:00:31.840
[Guest]: happy many of them to go along with the universalist argument when it comes to a so called a privilege

01:00:31.840 --> 01:00:36.000
[Guest]: or a benefit or something being given to a religious minority. But when you still turn

01:00:36.000 --> 01:00:40.920
[Guest]: around and say, look, I want to apply the same thing to you, then they have these, you

01:00:40.920 --> 01:00:46.240
[Guest]: know, historical reasons. And they'll say, well, you know, we've had a rough time for

01:00:46.240 --> 01:00:50.720
[Guest]: so long, we need this for some time, right? So there's no good faith here, right? They're

01:00:50.720 --> 01:01:00.920
[Guest]: not really interested in being fair. They're interested in presenting an argument for fairness,

01:01:00.920 --> 01:01:02.680
[Guest]: because it allows them to gain ground.

