01:03:05.640 --> 01:03:09.440
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen. I'm chatting with Sadanand Thume about the impact

01:03:09.440 --> 01:03:13.560
[Amit Varma]: of the 2019 elections and what exactly happened. At least we're supposed to talk about that,

01:03:13.560 --> 01:03:18.560
[Amit Varma]: but we spent an hour just contextualizing that discussion, talking about Modi and the

01:03:18.560 --> 01:03:26.440
[Amit Varma]: BJP and Hindutva and those intellectual traditions that brought us here and so on and so forth.

01:03:26.440 --> 01:03:31.800
[Amit Varma]: At what point did you realize, I mean, I've seen tweets by you after your travels through

01:03:31.800 --> 01:03:35.960
[Amit Varma]: UP and so on, where you said that, look, now I'm convinced having been to these places

01:03:35.960 --> 01:03:41.120
[Amit Varma]: that the BJP is going to win. At what point did you get convinced of that and why?

01:03:41.120 --> 01:03:51.280
[Guest]: In April, I went to early April, I traveled in Western UP. Actually, I was in I was going

01:03:51.280 --> 01:03:57.480
[Guest]: to Kathmandu for something. And I managed to sort of just steal a few days in Delhi

01:03:57.480 --> 01:04:04.080
[Guest]: and Western UP. And I was just sort of in mini poll mode where all I did, I mean, literally,

01:04:04.080 --> 01:04:13.320
[Guest]: if I met somebody didn't matter, Uber driver, room service guy, bellboy, paanwala, random

01:04:13.320 --> 01:04:18.760
[Guest]: woman in a wine bar, I mean, you name it. If I met you, probably the most irritating

01:04:18.760 --> 01:04:23.880
[Guest]: person in the city, I would like pinhole you and ask you what what you thought and what

01:04:23.880 --> 01:04:29.040
[Amit Varma]: random woman in a wine bar in UP. No, not in UP, that was in Delhi. So that was in Delhi.

01:04:29.040 --> 01:04:34.840
[Guest]: And then I went to travel in Western UP. And in the Jat belt, and you know, Baghpat, Shamli

01:04:34.840 --> 01:04:38.960
[Guest]: and some of these other places. And again, just, you know, talk to as many people as

01:04:38.960 --> 01:04:44.960
[Guest]: I could. And a couple of things emerged. And to me, the single most important, you know,

01:04:44.960 --> 01:04:49.400
[Guest]: you started out this podcast by talking about the various explanations, but there was one

01:04:49.400 --> 01:04:57.080
[Guest]: to me that was actually stood out above all of those. And it was simply the fact that

01:04:57.080 --> 01:05:04.400
[Guest]: virtually everybody I spoke with, thought of Modi as a good guy. That's what it was

01:05:04.400 --> 01:05:12.560
[Guest]: just a character thing. It was, you know, what, he's a hardworking person. He doesn't

01:05:12.560 --> 01:05:22.240
[Guest]: have family. He puts in all this effort every day for the country. And he deserves another

01:05:22.240 --> 01:05:30.480
[Guest]: chance. And more than anything else, that to me is was my dominant takeaway. And so

01:05:30.480 --> 01:05:35.400
[Guest]: at that point, I came I and and because you know, because of the nature of Delhi, you

01:05:35.400 --> 01:05:40.440
[Guest]: meet a lot of people who are migrants. So you know, I was talking to people from Rajasthan

01:05:40.440 --> 01:05:46.400
[Guest]: from Madhya Pradesh from UP in Delhi, apart from traveling in UP. And this wasn't even

01:05:46.400 --> 01:05:51.480
[Guest]: close on it. Right. And so you got the stories, you got the character part. And then I got

01:05:51.480 --> 01:05:58.520
[Guest]: stories about people who would actually receive the gas cylinder, people who had built a toilet

01:05:58.520 --> 01:06:05.600
[Guest]: in their village, guy who is a hilarious guy who had got a mudra loan in his wife's name

01:06:05.600 --> 01:06:13.960
[Guest]: and was really happy because he didn't think he ever had to pay it back. So there were

01:06:13.960 --> 01:06:21.680
[Guest]: all these stories in and, you know, in some cases, it was people who themselves had benefited

01:06:21.680 --> 01:06:26.360
[Guest]: or had been touched by some of these programs. But beyond that, there were people who just

01:06:26.360 --> 01:06:31.400
[Guest]: even if these programs had not touched them personally, the messaging had gone through

01:06:31.400 --> 01:06:38.000
[Guest]: and they had a feeling that this stuff is happening. And I left and you know, I wrote

01:06:38.000 --> 01:06:43.200
[Guest]: my column in the journal after that. And by the I was fairly convinced that this is, you

01:06:43.200 --> 01:06:51.120
[Guest]: know, this is something going on. And it you know, and not one person, not one person spoke

01:06:51.120 --> 01:06:56.280
[Guest]: like that about Rahul Gandhi. And so that was a sign. And then again, that was reinforced

01:06:56.280 --> 01:07:03.960
[Guest]: more when I came back in the middle of May, early May, and travel a little bit in eastern

01:07:03.960 --> 01:07:13.840
[Guest]: UP. And that was my sense that the battle of the narratives was completely won by Modi.

01:07:13.840 --> 01:07:20.440
[Guest]: Absolutely clearly won by Modi. And so to me, it was, you know, pretty clear. I didn't

01:07:20.440 --> 01:07:25.600
[Guest]: think I didn't believe as did most people didn't. I didn't think he'd get the BJP would

01:07:25.600 --> 01:07:28.800
[Guest]: get 303 seats. But I was pretty convinced he's coming back.

01:07:28.800 --> 01:07:33.600
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you know, much as Twitter elites made great fun of the interview Modi did with

01:07:33.600 --> 01:07:37.980
[Amit Varma]: Akshay Kumar, I thought it was a masterstroke because he might have been bullshitting his

01:07:37.980 --> 01:07:43.560
[Amit Varma]: way through it. But he came across as such a affable, nice guy, the kind of uncle you'd

01:07:43.560 --> 01:07:50.240
[Amit Varma]: want your kids to have. And just in terms of optics, it was it was a masterstroke. This

01:07:50.240 --> 01:07:54.160
[Amit Varma]: is you know, you spoke of the battle of narratives. And there's this interesting column by Shekhar

01:07:54.160 --> 01:08:00.120
[Amit Varma]: Gupta, I just read today in the print, where he says that the dominant sort of conflicting

01:08:00.120 --> 01:08:06.160
[Amit Varma]: narratives for the last 20-25 years were Mandal versus Mandir, right? Where on the one hand,

01:08:06.160 --> 01:08:11.040
[Amit Varma]: you have all these other parties which are exploiting caste divisions and caste identities

01:08:11.040 --> 01:08:17.700
[Amit Varma]: and you know, trying to build vote banks on the basis of that. And as a counter to that,

01:08:17.700 --> 01:08:22.520
[Amit Varma]: you have the BJP effort of the Mandir narrative where they're trying to subsume many of those

01:08:22.520 --> 01:08:28.720
[Amit Varma]: identities within a broad Hindu identity and, you know, making that case. And Shekhar's

01:08:28.720 --> 01:08:34.360
[Amit Varma]: point was that now that battle is irrelevant. It's not about Mandal, it's not even about

01:08:34.360 --> 01:08:39.820
[Amit Varma]: Mandir, it's about Modi. That and which seems to, you know, hark to exactly what you said

01:08:39.820 --> 01:08:43.560
[Amit Varma]: now that it's a personality thing. I mean, Milan Vaishnav just wrote a piece for the

01:08:43.560 --> 01:08:48.920
[Amit Varma]: Washington Post today, which I retweeted where Milan pointed to a survey which shows that

01:08:48.920 --> 01:08:53.120
[Amit Varma]: the number of people who would have voted for BJP if Modi was not the man in charge

01:08:53.120 --> 01:08:54.120
[Amit Varma]: is far less.

01:08:54.120 --> 01:08:57.120
[Amit Varma]: 32%, I think something like that. 32% less.

01:08:57.120 --> 01:09:02.720
[Amit Varma]: Is far, far less. And Modi made that kind of difference. And is this a similar personality

01:09:02.720 --> 01:09:08.200
[Amit Varma]: cult to Indira Gandhi? If so, how did it come about? Is it happenstance for Modi? Or was

01:09:08.200 --> 01:09:14.640
[Amit Varma]: it actually planned by the great strategist, Ramit Shah? You know, and how does one counter

01:09:14.640 --> 01:09:15.640
[Guest]: it?

01:09:15.640 --> 01:09:21.360
[Guest]: Well, I think it was happenstance. It was carefully planned and extremely well resourced.

01:09:21.360 --> 01:09:26.880
[Guest]: The BJP is much richer than any other party in India, possibly richer than most parties

01:09:26.880 --> 01:09:32.920
[Guest]: in the world. So they certainly had the resources and the ability to get that message across.

01:09:32.920 --> 01:09:36.240
[Guest]: And you know, anecdotally, again, you know, it's sort of distasteful to ask people what

01:09:36.240 --> 01:09:40.880
[Guest]: their cost is. But you know, when you're reporting in the Hindi heartland, you kind of hold your

01:09:40.880 --> 01:09:46.560
[Guest]: nose and you you do sort of ask just because that's how the narrative is set by, by journalists.

01:09:46.560 --> 01:09:54.760
[Guest]: And it was not uncommon at all to come across people who were from subcastes that were not

01:09:54.760 --> 01:10:00.480
[Guest]: traditionally seen as BJP voters, who were just voting for Modi. And they just like Modi.

01:10:00.480 --> 01:10:07.600
[Guest]: And this is like, he's a good guy. He's the person I trust. He's the he's a strong leader.

01:10:07.600 --> 01:10:13.000
[Guest]: So in many ways, the messaging, if you look at it, the messaging has been extremely simple.

01:10:13.000 --> 01:10:18.800
[Guest]: And so the sort of things that we make fun of, right, the sort of things that people

01:10:18.800 --> 01:10:23.360
[Guest]: make fun of on Twitter, right, like this whole thing he did on the last day of voting, where

01:10:23.360 --> 01:10:28.000
[Guest]: he, you know, wore that ridiculous cape and then had the guy under the sink. I mean, come

01:10:28.000 --> 01:10:31.920
[Guest]: on, it's really funny. And so right, you could have done a whole sort of, if we had a sort

01:10:31.920 --> 01:10:36.040
[Guest]: of more of a comic tradition on television, you could have done a whole skit on how, you

01:10:36.040 --> 01:10:41.320
[Guest]: know, here's this sort of vain guy who has like the camera following him everywhere.

01:10:41.320 --> 01:10:45.680
[Unknown]: And everyone made fun of it. And I think it's fine. But that's the kind of thing that actually

01:10:45.680 --> 01:10:51.840
[Guest]: boomerangs badly. I'm not saying we shouldn't have made fun of it because hey, but boomerang

01:10:51.840 --> 01:11:01.360
[Guest]: so badly because at one level, you have most people who are in fact, connecting with him.

01:11:01.360 --> 01:11:08.280
[Guest]: Many of them are living vicariously through that moment. So for them, he is this deeply

01:11:08.280 --> 01:11:14.640
[Guest]: spiritual man who is connected to the religious traditions of this land. And he is out there

01:11:14.640 --> 01:11:22.040
[Guest]: doing something deeply meaningful. And then not only is that something that they're connecting

01:11:22.040 --> 01:11:29.120
[Guest]: with, and they have to put up with, you know, a bunch of English speaking, faithless people,

01:11:29.120 --> 01:11:37.540
[Guest]: atheists, God knows what, beefeaters, and you know, out there making fun of him. Right.

01:11:37.540 --> 01:11:40.480
[Guest]: And so in fact, it's sort of it boomerangs.

01:11:40.480 --> 01:11:45.840
[Guest]: Sankarshar Thakur actually had a piece in the Telegraph today, where he also made that

01:11:45.840 --> 01:11:52.080
[Guest]: point and I think it's absolutely correct. And that's where Modi has been a masterful

01:11:52.080 --> 01:11:59.880
[Guest]: communicator. He's not trying to communicate to you or me. He realizes that we are ultimately

01:11:59.880 --> 01:12:06.760
[Guest]: irrelevant. And the only reason the Congress Party folks cared about us a little bit was

01:12:06.760 --> 01:12:10.880
[Guest]: because they bumped into us at cocktail parties, but Modi is not going to cocktail parties.

01:12:10.880 --> 01:12:16.920
[Guest]: So there's no danger of bumping into us. And so that's very, that's a powerful insight

01:12:16.920 --> 01:12:23.800
[Guest]: he and Amit Shah have as politicians. And you can see how that narrative was crafted,

01:12:23.800 --> 01:12:29.400
[Guest]: how that image was crafted of the hardworking man. And in fairness to him, there's an element

01:12:29.400 --> 01:12:34.040
[Guest]: of truth in it. I mean, you've talked about this, the biographical element, the story

01:12:34.040 --> 01:12:40.040
[Guest]: is incredibly powerful, right in a society that is as stratified. I mean, this is the

01:12:40.040 --> 01:12:42.920
[Guest]: thing, right? You don't have to agree with everything he does. And you can criticize

01:12:42.920 --> 01:12:47.880
[Guest]: him while conceding. And it's an incredibly powerful story in this kind of stratified

01:12:47.880 --> 01:12:57.680
[Guest]: society where so much of your life trajectory is determined by the accident of birth, right?

01:12:57.680 --> 01:13:01.760
[Guest]: You and I are having this conversation in English, because we were born into certain

01:13:01.760 --> 01:13:06.840
[Guest]: families, it was easy for us, we didn't do anything special to learn it, right? It was

01:13:06.840 --> 01:13:13.480
[Guest]: just the luck of the draw. And so many of our life chances end up being, you know, determined

01:13:13.480 --> 01:13:20.360
[Guest]: by just this luck, just this chance. So in such a stratified society, for someone to

01:13:20.360 --> 01:13:25.200
[Guest]: emerge with no advantages, he doesn't have the advantage of class, he doesn't have the

01:13:25.200 --> 01:13:32.920
[Guest]: advantage of cost, he doesn't have the advantage of Godfathers, he just he makes it through

01:13:32.920 --> 01:13:38.080
[Guest]: hard work, and ambition, and smarts. And it's an incredibly powerful story.

01:13:38.080 --> 01:13:46.960
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you kind of spoke about, you know, how he's good material for comedy, and so

01:13:46.960 --> 01:13:50.400
[Amit Varma]: on and so forth. And you should check out TikTok sometime, which I'm kind of addicted

01:13:50.400 --> 01:13:51.400
[Amit Varma]: to. Have you checked out TikTok?

01:13:51.400 --> 01:13:55.840
[Guest]: I'm keeping away. My life has already been ruined by Twitter. I can't afford TikTok.

01:13:55.840 --> 01:14:00.480
[Amit Varma]: It is incredibly though I'd love to see you start a TikTok channel. That would be quite

01:14:00.480 --> 01:14:01.480
[Amit Varma]: something.

01:14:01.480 --> 01:14:04.360
[Amit Varma]: I'd love to see some of my dance moves.

01:14:04.360 --> 01:14:08.640
[Amit Varma]: Going back to kind of what you said earlier is, you know, for example, about people who

01:14:08.640 --> 01:14:12.880
[Amit Varma]: about subcastes and groups, which would otherwise not have voted for him voting for him, you

01:14:12.880 --> 01:14:20.080
[Amit Varma]: know, I mean, in 2014, what he did famously do was that he exploited intra caste resentments.

01:14:20.080 --> 01:14:25.240
[Amit Varma]: For example, in UP, he reached out to non jatav dalits and to non yadav OBCs and so

01:14:25.240 --> 01:14:30.640
[Amit Varma]: on and got them on his side. And he managed to expand those sort of alliances over time.

01:14:30.640 --> 01:14:36.320
[Amit Varma]: And just today, I think I saw a tweet thread from Jignesh Mewani, the Dalit leader in Gujarat

01:14:36.320 --> 01:14:41.440
[Amit Varma]: and who was kind of bemoaning and saying, I don't understand it that so many Dalits

01:14:41.440 --> 01:14:46.400
[Amit Varma]: actually seem to have voted for Modi. And you know, there have been Dalit scholars in

01:14:46.400 --> 01:14:50.400
[Amit Varma]: the past who said that, you know, the Dalit party in India today is basically the BJP,

01:14:50.400 --> 01:14:59.680
[Amit Varma]: which seems, you know, like a masterful achievement of political strategy. And coming, you know,

01:14:59.680 --> 01:15:04.480
[Amit Varma]: in coming to that, like there is one way where you can think that this rise of Hindutva and

01:15:04.480 --> 01:15:08.800
[Amit Varma]: this rise of the BJP, especially given the incompetence of the opposition was inevitable.

01:15:08.800 --> 01:15:12.920
[Amit Varma]: But another way of looking at it is to, you know, do the whole great man theory of history

01:15:12.920 --> 01:15:19.200
[Amit Varma]: thing and say that no, Amit Shah is really the strategic genius who's made all of this

01:15:19.200 --> 01:15:20.960
[Amit Varma]: possible. How do you sort of look at that?

01:15:20.960 --> 01:15:25.320
[Guest]: I guess maybe a bit of both, right? I mean, for sure, you have Amit Shah's, you know,

01:15:25.320 --> 01:15:32.840
[Guest]: ability to craft these very sort of carefully plotted alliances and look at the math of

01:15:32.840 --> 01:15:38.640
[Guest]: these things with great granularity, then you have Modi's undeniable charisma, his powerful

01:15:38.640 --> 01:15:44.560
[Guest]: biography. I mean, you also have the fact, frankly, that the both the Lohiite parties

01:15:44.560 --> 01:15:50.080
[Guest]: and the Dalit parties, basically the SP and the BSP are, you know, they're a travesty.

01:15:50.080 --> 01:15:55.520
[Guest]: I mean, Mulan Singh Yadav's son's driving around in a Lamborghini. These are not people

01:15:55.520 --> 01:16:02.640
[Guest]: who have maintained any kind of standard of probity in public life. What are they in it

01:16:02.640 --> 01:16:08.120
[Guest]: for? Right. And that's the question I ask. You can disagree with the BJP guys and I disagree

01:16:08.120 --> 01:16:13.760
[Guest]: with them. But, you know, for example, as the results from Amethi were coming in and,

01:16:13.760 --> 01:16:18.440
[Guest]: you know, it was it was getting late. There were a bunch of workers who were there as

01:16:18.440 --> 01:16:24.680
[Guest]: Smriti Irani supporters. Right. They were in the booth. They are they're driven by something.

01:16:24.680 --> 01:16:30.720
[Guest]: They wake up in the morning and they are energized because they believe in something. What do

01:16:30.720 --> 01:16:36.720
[Guest]: these other parties believe in? What do they believe in beyond making their own family

01:16:36.720 --> 01:16:43.200
[Guest]: or kinship group wealthy or powerful? Right. I mean, what was the SP rule in, you know,

01:16:43.200 --> 01:16:47.680
[Guest]: in UP? They did some good things. They made some roads and so on. But a lot of it was

01:16:47.680 --> 01:16:52.400
[Guest]: about empowering, you know, gundas from their community to do whatever they wanted. So I

01:16:52.400 --> 01:16:58.480
[Guest]: think the moral center has really fallen out of these parties. And that has that that is

01:16:58.480 --> 01:17:03.280
[Guest]: one thing that, you know, that's just made for the BJP. And so that's why you don't get

01:17:03.280 --> 01:17:08.360
[Guest]: the kind of transference. Right. So this is the assumption of the Gatbandhan was that,

01:17:08.360 --> 01:17:11.840
[Guest]: look, we're together. So all the Dalits are going to vote for the SP candidates and all

01:17:11.840 --> 01:17:18.040
[Guest]: the Yadavs are going to vote for the BSP candidates. Ashok Varshney even wrote a piece in the Indian

01:17:18.040 --> 01:17:23.600
[Guest]: Express where he sort of broke out all the math. But that's not how it works, because

01:17:23.600 --> 01:17:31.320
[Guest]: the BJP has, for the Hindu majority, especially in the Hindi heartland, they've been able

01:17:31.320 --> 01:17:39.920
[Guest]: to craft a kind of moral message. The tragedy of that message is that it involves a complete

01:17:39.920 --> 01:17:46.240
[Guest]: lack of compassion or any kind of connection to things like minority rights and the things

01:17:46.240 --> 01:17:47.960
[Amit Varma]: that we talked about.

01:17:47.960 --> 01:17:54.200
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one of the things that I kept remarking on as these elections came close

01:17:54.200 --> 01:17:59.720
[Amit Varma]: was that the BJP seemed to behave as if history ended in 2014. They would not talk about the

01:17:59.720 --> 01:18:03.320
[Amit Varma]: five years the governance records of that time would keep going back to Nehru did this

01:18:03.320 --> 01:18:09.360
[Amit Varma]: and Rajiv Gandhi did this and so on. But the Congress on the other hand behaved as if history

01:18:09.360 --> 01:18:15.760
[Amit Varma]: began in 2014, where they would ignore their past misgovernance over 70 years where in

01:18:15.760 --> 01:18:20.660
[Amit Varma]: fact when Rahul Gandhi would be asked about things like bank nationalization or the horrors

01:18:20.660 --> 01:18:26.800
[Amit Varma]: of the emergency or the horrors of 1984, which he was aware he at one point denied that his

01:18:26.800 --> 01:18:31.840
[Amit Varma]: family had a role. And they were sort of in denial of all that in the past and basing

01:18:31.840 --> 01:18:37.360
[Amit Varma]: everything on Modi is a bad guy, don't vote for Modi, vote for us without sort of laying

01:18:37.360 --> 01:18:42.760
[Amit Varma]: out their own vision. And, you know, as as the elections came, they did lay out a little

01:18:42.760 --> 01:18:47.480
[Amit Varma]: bit of their own vision. And some of it was old school welfarism of the Garibi Hatao type

01:18:47.480 --> 01:18:52.600
[Amit Varma]: like the whole Niay campaign. And some of it was just hypocritical in the sense and

01:18:52.600 --> 01:18:56.320
[Amit Varma]: I asked Salman about this in the episode I did with him as well, that you know, they

01:18:56.320 --> 01:19:02.160
[Amit Varma]: had a thing in the manifesto about we'll have directly elected mayors will be actually empowered

01:19:02.160 --> 01:19:06.360
[Amit Varma]: to do local governance, which is great, but that is a state subject, the Congress is in

01:19:06.360 --> 01:19:11.880
[Amit Varma]: power in so many states, and they've honestly done jack about it. You know, in fact, a lot

01:19:11.880 --> 01:19:15.840
[Amit Varma]: of what is in their manifesto for 2019 could have been implemented by state governments

01:19:15.840 --> 01:19:19.920
[Amit Varma]: in different ways. And they've done absolutely nothing. This is just posturing to Twitter

01:19:19.920 --> 01:19:25.120
[Amit Varma]: elites, what has gone wrong with the Congress, right, even after this heavy defeat, they

01:19:25.120 --> 01:19:27.800
[Amit Varma]: are still sticking to failed and competent leaders.

01:19:27.800 --> 01:19:32.280
[Guest]: I mean, we need a whole different podcast on what has gone wrong with Congress. But

01:19:32.280 --> 01:19:37.320
[Guest]: you know, to start with, you know, in some ways, if you if you think about the big narrative

01:19:37.320 --> 01:19:42.920
[Guest]: about India since 1947, you know, despite the fact that, you know, we've done pretty

01:19:42.920 --> 01:19:48.720
[Guest]: well, relatively speaking, since 1991. All in all, if you step back, and you look at

01:19:48.720 --> 01:19:55.120
[Guest]: India 1947 to 2019, I think it's fair to say that we haven't done as well as we should

01:19:55.120 --> 01:20:00.340
[Guest]: have and that many other places have done much better. And this plays into Modi's hands,

01:20:00.340 --> 01:20:06.320
[Guest]: because the story that Congress has to tell voters is that, look, actually, we did a pretty

01:20:06.320 --> 01:20:15.120
[Guest]: good job. And they try to tell that story by pointing to the IIMs and ISRO and the IITs.

01:20:15.120 --> 01:20:18.760
[Guest]: And certainly there's been progress, no question about it, right? And if you're any, if you

01:20:18.760 --> 01:20:23.200
[Guest]: look at per capita income, literacy or anything, there's been progress. But you can't really

01:20:23.200 --> 01:20:29.400
[Guest]: make the case that they did a fantastic job, right? The Nehru-Gandhi family did not do

01:20:29.400 --> 01:20:34.680
[Guest]: for India, what Lee Kuan Yew did, what the Lees did for Singapore. They just didn't,

01:20:34.680 --> 01:20:41.500
[Guest]: right? And Modi is able to wield that as a club. And so their defenses just come across

01:20:41.500 --> 01:20:49.480
[Guest]: as weak, right? It's like, no, look, we actually helped build the whatever x institution or

01:20:49.480 --> 01:20:55.120
[Guest]: whatever. And so that's part of the problem. The other part of the problem is that, you

01:20:55.120 --> 01:21:02.000
[Guest]: know, Rahul Gandhi is in, he's basically European socialist, right? NIAI is a handout scheme.

01:21:02.000 --> 01:21:07.120
[Guest]: And I believe this is truly who he is. I think he's being sincere. This is how he sees the

01:21:07.120 --> 01:21:11.680
[Guest]: world, right? You go back, you know, go back to 10 years, and he was talking about the

01:21:11.680 --> 01:21:16.880
[Guest]: two Indias and how he was going to fight for the tribals of Orissa and so on.

01:21:16.880 --> 01:21:20.960
[Amit Varma]: It's complete zero sum thinking. He doesn't really have any deeper understanding of economics

01:21:20.960 --> 01:21:25.440
[Guest]: or policy. But to the degree that he has any kind of instincts, those are his instincts.

01:21:25.440 --> 01:21:30.760
[Guest]: The problem is that when you are a fourth or fifth or whatever, depending on how you

01:21:30.760 --> 01:21:39.320
[Guest]: want to count a generation, dentist, you really can't play the I'm the Messiah of the poor

01:21:39.320 --> 01:21:46.420
[Guest]: game better than the tea seller. You can't, you may think you can, but you're delusional

01:21:46.420 --> 01:21:54.600
[Guest]: if you think you can. And this is the fundamental problem. He is not an authentic bearer of

01:21:54.600 --> 01:21:59.560
[Guest]: the message that he wants to bear. Quite apart from the fact that he has sort of other problems.

01:21:59.560 --> 01:22:04.720
[Guest]: He doesn't have the most basic political skills. He's an anti politician in some ways, and

01:22:04.720 --> 01:22:12.400
[Guest]: we can get into that. But the story that the Congress could sell is the story of competence,

01:22:12.400 --> 01:22:17.560
[Guest]: relative competence, to the extent that they might do stupid things, but they wouldn't

01:22:17.560 --> 01:22:26.400
[Unknown]: do nutty demon, right? So it was, they would, they might, you know, screw up on interfaith

01:22:26.400 --> 01:22:31.560
[Guest]: relations, but you wouldn't have Yogi Adityanath as chief minister of UP. So their story was

01:22:31.560 --> 01:22:37.300
[Guest]: really of look, we are where the grownups here. And that may not have been a compelling

01:22:37.300 --> 01:22:40.600
[Guest]: enough story because the country happens to be a large chunks of the country are in love

01:22:40.600 --> 01:22:46.460
[Guest]: with Narendra Modi. I'm not saying that I would have won the election. But this idea

01:22:46.460 --> 01:22:51.880
[Guest]: that this guy born with a silver spoon in his mouth, not just a silver spoon, the whole

01:22:51.880 --> 01:23:00.600
[Guest]: cutlery set, right? This, this guy is somehow going to be the Messiah of the poor, and he's

01:23:00.600 --> 01:23:03.920
[Guest]: going to take on the chaiwala. I mean, it's preposterous.

01:23:03.920 --> 01:23:10.200
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I'm really amused by the fact that a lot of my friends who call themselves progressives

01:23:10.200 --> 01:23:16.840
[Amit Varma]: actually support a guy who is where he is only because he was born into extreme privilege,

01:23:16.840 --> 01:23:22.600
[Amit Varma]: and because of power structures in his party, prevent others from actually rising up through

01:23:22.600 --> 01:23:27.640
[Amit Varma]: the ranks. And they support this guy. And to me, it simply doesn't compute. It's classic

01:23:27.640 --> 01:23:32.160
[Amit Varma]: hypocrisy. I mean, I've said in the past that, you know, a couple of years back, I'd said

01:23:32.160 --> 01:23:36.800
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, those who support Gandhi today are helping Modi win in 2019. And similarly

01:23:36.800 --> 01:23:41.080
[Amit Varma]: today, I think those who are helping Rahul Gandhi stay in power are helping Modi win

01:23:41.080 --> 01:23:45.560
[Amit Varma]: 2024. But, you know, tell me something. I mean, it's if the Congress is a dying party

01:23:45.560 --> 01:23:51.160
[Amit Varma]: and the Gandhis help it along, that's fine. But a healthy democracy needs an opposition.

01:23:51.160 --> 01:23:56.080
[Amit Varma]: Where are the possible avenues and opposition can emerge from?

01:23:56.080 --> 01:24:00.840
[Guest]: It's a tough question. And I think that that's, you know, the only argument you in fact have

01:24:00.840 --> 01:24:06.960
[Guest]: for keeping the Congress alive at this moment in time is that without them, there'd be even

01:24:06.960 --> 01:24:13.200
[Guest]: less of an opposition. There's no meaningful political opposition, even with the Congress

01:24:13.200 --> 01:24:21.080
[Guest]: with their 52 seats, or whatever, and in the Lok Sabha, the media has been a large chunks

01:24:21.080 --> 01:24:26.640
[Guest]: of the media have been co-opted. And the parts that have not been co-opted can probably be

01:24:26.640 --> 01:24:36.240
[Guest]: safely ignored. The courts do have a measure of independence, though. But again, I think

01:24:36.240 --> 01:24:42.760
[Guest]: a powerful executive with five years ahead of it would have enough tools to sort of slowly

01:24:42.760 --> 01:24:47.640
[Guest]: and gradually make sure that the sort of people that they approve of are in the courts. And

01:24:47.640 --> 01:24:52.760
[Guest]: we've already seen, for instance, in the last five years, the collapse of any kind of case

01:24:52.760 --> 01:24:59.080
[Guest]: where the victim happens to be a minority and the accused happens to be someone associated

01:24:59.080 --> 01:25:07.800
[Guest]: with the Sangh Parivar. So you already sort of see the courts under pressure. What does

01:25:07.800 --> 01:25:14.520
[Guest]: that leave? Whose bureaucracy has been politicized? So I think we are in uncharted territory here.

01:25:14.520 --> 01:25:20.600
[Guest]: We really have, we're in a place where, you know, the old argument and the old complaint

01:25:20.600 --> 01:25:30.160
[Guest]: about India used to be that, look, things move too slowly. There's no foot on the accelerator.

01:25:30.160 --> 01:25:34.960
[Guest]: And I think now we have to sort of start thinking of India and imagine what it's like to have

01:25:34.960 --> 01:25:40.120
[Guest]: no brakes. And that's what's going on now. We have no brakes. There are things that have

01:25:40.120 --> 01:25:44.900
[Guest]: happened in the last five years that we would not have been able to imagine. I would not

01:25:44.900 --> 01:25:50.320
[Guest]: have been able to imagine that someone like Hemant Karkare, who was a national hero, loses

01:25:50.320 --> 01:26:01.960
[Guest]: his life fighting Pakistani terrorists on 26-11 in Mumbai, can have his reputation savaged

01:26:01.960 --> 01:26:11.600
[Guest]: and soiled overnight on social media, because the BJP has decided to nominate Sadhvi Pragya.

01:26:11.600 --> 01:26:17.560
[Guest]: So even if people who have this sort of traditional set of protections, right, civil service,

01:26:17.560 --> 01:26:25.480
[Guest]: yes, gallantry award, people like that, their reputations are no longer safe. So in many

01:26:25.480 --> 01:26:32.960
[Guest]: ways, we're just in a place where, you know, virtually anything is possible. And some of

01:26:32.960 --> 01:26:36.400
[Guest]: this stuff is probably outside the realms of our imagination.

01:26:36.400 --> 01:26:39.920
[Amit Varma]: Sort of moving on back to, you know, leaving the opposition aside and just moving back

01:26:39.920 --> 01:26:45.960
[Amit Varma]: to the BJP and this government. You'd mentioned earlier about the massive amount of resources

01:26:45.960 --> 01:26:50.520
[Amit Varma]: that they have. And in fact, this is a point, say, Raghu Karnad made through an excellent

01:26:50.520 --> 01:26:55.400
[Amit Varma]: video a while back on YouTube, and he persistently drives this point home on Twitter that the

01:26:55.400 --> 01:27:00.680
[Amit Varma]: BJP just have so many more resources than anyone else to push their narrative. And that

01:27:00.680 --> 01:27:05.200
[Amit Varma]: is a massive part of their victory as well. And at one hand, of course, you don't know

01:27:05.200 --> 01:27:08.680
[Amit Varma]: which way the causation also goes. Part of the reason they have these resources is that

01:27:08.680 --> 01:27:13.400
[Amit Varma]: the narrative is winning out. But then also it's a question of maybe network effects.

01:27:13.400 --> 01:27:18.160
[Amit Varma]: Power attracts money, money buys more power, and so on and so forth. Is that something

01:27:18.160 --> 01:27:19.160
[Amit Varma]: that worries you?

01:27:19.160 --> 01:27:25.240
[Guest]: I mean, beyond that, look at the evil genius of it. They come up with these electoral bonds,

01:27:25.240 --> 01:27:30.760
[Unknown]: which basically make funding completely opaque. And they sell it to people as a reform. I

01:27:30.760 --> 01:27:39.680
[Unknown]: mean, it is, you've got to at one level admire it. Look, I've cleaned up electoral funding.

01:27:39.680 --> 01:27:44.360
[Unknown]: How have you cleaned it up? I've cleaned it up by introducing these completely opaque

01:27:44.360 --> 01:27:52.040
[Guest]: bonds, and of which 90% or 95% of them will never come to my party. In theory, you don't

01:27:52.040 --> 01:27:55.980
[Guest]: know who gave the money, but you can be pretty darn sure that the people who are buying these

01:27:55.980 --> 01:28:01.880
[Guest]: bonds believe that the parties know exactly who they're giving the money to. And so in

01:28:01.880 --> 01:28:07.440
[Guest]: some ways, it's also this moment, right, where the Indian economy has grown to a certain

01:28:07.440 --> 01:28:15.640
[Guest]: size and elections have become so expensive. And this party that is very well organized,

01:28:15.640 --> 01:28:20.520
[Guest]: and absolutely ruthless when it comes to winning elections, has seized the reins of power.

01:28:20.520 --> 01:28:27.920
[Guest]: And now it has this first mover advantage that gives it such a huge leg up over anybody

01:28:27.920 --> 01:28:32.440
[Guest]: else. And, you know, it really comes back to 2014, where, you know, at one point, Congress

01:28:32.440 --> 01:28:35.640
[Guest]: would have had those advantages, they didn't have the ruthlessness, they didn't have the

01:28:35.640 --> 01:28:41.000
[Guest]: imagination to really press their point. You know, they were shambolic and disorganized.

01:28:41.000 --> 01:28:45.000
[Guest]: These guys have power now. I mean, you never know in politics, of course, things, people

01:28:45.000 --> 01:28:52.380
[Guest]: think go up and down. But given the kind of system that is being put in place, both in

01:28:52.380 --> 01:28:58.160
[Guest]: terms of, you know, traditional media, such as television, the fake news factories that

01:28:58.160 --> 01:29:03.080
[Guest]: are set up where, you know, basically, you know, there's just, you know, there's no difference

01:29:03.080 --> 01:29:08.160
[Guest]: between, you know, there are people out there, you know, who genuinely believe that Nehru

01:29:08.160 --> 01:29:13.920
[Guest]: was this lascivious man, because they've seen a picture of him pecking his niece on the

01:29:13.920 --> 01:29:21.040
[Guest]: cheek at an airport. Right? There are people who really genuinely believe that Nehru had

01:29:21.040 --> 01:29:26.800
[Guest]: Stalin put Bose into some gulag in Siberia, right? There are people, this stuff is believed,

01:29:26.800 --> 01:29:31.320
[Guest]: right? I've met people in Uttar Pradesh, who, you know, tell me that, you know, Nehru's

01:29:31.320 --> 01:29:37.440
[Guest]: great grandfather was a Muslim. I mean, this is just so what is true and what is not true.

01:29:37.440 --> 01:29:42.800
[Guest]: They have an ability to just to dominate both traditional media, and then using, you know,

01:29:42.800 --> 01:29:46.840
[Guest]: WhatsApp and these fake news sites that they've set up, like postcard news, also just put

01:29:46.840 --> 01:29:52.440
[Guest]: out misinformation. And then they have the resources to amplify this. And you have this

01:29:52.440 --> 01:30:01.720
[Guest]: completely inept opposition, you have the fact that a large section of our punditocracy

01:30:01.720 --> 01:30:06.400
[Guest]: will very happily get co opted. I mean, the best example for me of that is all the sort

01:30:06.400 --> 01:30:12.240
[Guest]: of self professed libertarians singing the praises of demon. I mean, it's sort of it's

01:30:12.240 --> 01:30:13.240
[Unknown]: surreal.

01:30:13.240 --> 01:30:20.320
[Amit Varma]: To bring libertarians into it is absolutely shocking. I'd written a piece about this called,

01:30:20.320 --> 01:30:24.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, beware of the useful idiots talking about sort of the intellectuals who supported

01:30:24.960 --> 01:30:30.240
[Amit Varma]: Modi, even long after it became obvious that he is what he's shown himself to be. And in

01:30:30.240 --> 01:30:33.960
[Amit Varma]: fact, in that, I don't know if you read it, but I held you out as an example of intellectual

01:30:33.960 --> 01:30:38.360
[Amit Varma]: honesty, because you kind of changed your mind there. But you know, just fake news.

01:30:38.360 --> 01:30:42.600
[Amit Varma]: I mean, we live in an age of bullshit in the sense that Harry Frankford defined the term

01:30:42.600 --> 01:30:47.160
[Amit Varma]: bullshit, right, which is that a person who lies knows what the truth is. And he chooses

01:30:47.160 --> 01:30:51.520
[Amit Varma]: to lie to divert people's attention from that. A person who bullshit doesn't care what the

01:30:51.520 --> 01:30:56.120
[Amit Varma]: truth is. He's just winging it. He's saying whatever he feels like at the moment, and

01:30:56.120 --> 01:31:01.720
[Amit Varma]: it may or may not be true. And, you know, Modi is a classic bullshitter. And it works

01:31:01.720 --> 01:31:07.160
[Amit Varma]: for him in the sense that even if you see that much maligned interview of him, where

01:31:07.160 --> 01:31:13.400
[Amit Varma]: he speaks about how clouds sort of stop radar, right. And now the thing is, by making fun

01:31:13.400 --> 01:31:18.320
[Amit Varma]: of him, we're just like getting him you're just you're just increasing his vote margin

01:31:18.320 --> 01:31:19.320
[Amit Varma]: even more.

01:31:19.320 --> 01:31:22.800
[Amit Varma]: Because number one, people don't care about the facts. And number two, what he does well

01:31:22.800 --> 01:31:28.560
[Amit Varma]: in that interview is he comes across as this folksy likeable as this guy with folksy wisdom

01:31:28.560 --> 01:31:34.040
[Amit Varma]: and he's, you know, likeable and all of that and that image has nothing to do with whether

01:31:34.040 --> 01:31:39.860
[Amit Varma]: he's talking sense or not. And this is something which I think a lot of people just haven't

01:31:39.860 --> 01:31:42.800
[Amit Varma]: figured out that we live in an age where facts don't matter.

01:31:42.800 --> 01:31:46.000
[Guest]: And I don't think it's just bullshitting. I don't think it's a question of, well, I'm

01:31:46.000 --> 01:31:50.040
[Guest]: talking about the larger machine, not Modi specifically. I don't think this is a question

01:31:50.040 --> 01:31:55.160
[Guest]: of not caring. The lies in the fabrications are very carefully crafted. Again, it's the

01:31:55.160 --> 01:32:00.760
[Guest]: same thing. It comes down to sort of like the cloud. They are preposterous to us. If

01:32:00.760 --> 01:32:04.360
[Guest]: you're educated, you think this is like, it's actually you can't read this stuff without

01:32:04.360 --> 01:32:14.720
[Unknown]: laughing, right? Nehru's grandfather was Ghiyasuddin Ghazi. It's insane stuff. But this stuff

01:32:14.720 --> 01:32:24.300
[Guest]: is believed, right? So and it's all very well constructed. It all goes in a particular direction.

01:32:24.300 --> 01:32:29.760
[Guest]: And they have at this point, they have done such a number on Rahul Gandhi. I don't think

01:32:29.760 --> 01:32:35.880
[Guest]: his political reputation is recoverable. And it's because they didn't have the capacity

01:32:35.880 --> 01:32:41.080
[Guest]: to take this seriously. So they're not just bullshitting, they have targets. They figure

01:32:41.080 --> 01:32:45.440
[Guest]: out who they want to go after. I mean, at one point, it was kind of, we had the sort

01:32:45.440 --> 01:32:49.560
[Guest]: of lower end of this, I sort of, at some one point, I found that there were all kinds of

01:32:49.560 --> 01:32:56.160
[Guest]: people who were on Twitter who would attack me. And they will always accuse me of taking

01:32:56.160 --> 01:33:02.480
[Guest]: either 2 lakh rupees or 5 lakh rupees from the from the Congress. Of course, they haven't

01:33:02.480 --> 01:33:06.400
[Guest]: read the fact that I'm, I've been critical of Congress for more than 10 years and still

01:33:06.400 --> 01:33:10.240
[Guest]: remain critical of Congress. But anyway, they were like, you're on the Congress payroll.

01:33:10.240 --> 01:33:15.620
[Guest]: And I was kind of I couldn't understand why they only ever accused me either of taking

01:33:15.620 --> 01:33:20.760
[Unknown]: 2 lakh rupees or 5 lakh rupees. And I was just like, why are there no 4? And it's kind

01:33:20.760 --> 01:33:24.480
[Amit Varma]: of an insult that they're accusing you of being so cheap, like you can sell yourself

01:33:24.480 --> 01:33:30.640
[Unknown]: for 5 lakhs. Well, 5 lakhs is a lot of money for me. I think it was a recurring thing.

01:33:30.640 --> 01:33:34.920
[Guest]: It wasn't just wasn't a one time thing. So I was sort of like, why? Why do they only

01:33:34.920 --> 01:33:43.080
[Guest]: have these two numbers? Why don't they have, you know, three and a half? And it turns out

01:33:43.080 --> 01:33:47.800
[Guest]: there was in one of their fake news sites, someone had written a story where they hadn't

01:33:47.800 --> 01:33:53.720
[Guest]: attached names on put names there. But they put out this story saying that Cambridge Analytica

01:33:53.720 --> 01:34:03.440
[Guest]: has hired, I don't know, 125 intellectuals to defame Modiji. And my hunch is that there

01:34:03.440 --> 01:34:09.560
[Guest]: was another version of this, which is probably on WhatsApp, where they had sort of lists

01:34:09.560 --> 01:34:17.160
[Unknown]: of people. And people believe this stuff, right? I mean, this is just someone just writing

01:34:17.160 --> 01:34:23.920
[Guest]: a column somewhere, and they care enough to do this. Imagine if you're actually a real

01:34:23.920 --> 01:34:29.440
[Unknown]: opponent. This is terrifying, right? Look at Nitish Kumar. You're doing yourself a disservice.

01:34:29.440 --> 01:34:35.920
[Guest]: You're a real opponent. He was just, you know, one day he was being battered every day on

01:34:35.920 --> 01:34:41.360
[Guest]: television as for corruption, and his whole image was Mr. Clean. And then suddenly he's,

01:34:41.360 --> 01:34:45.240
[Guest]: you know, he switches and then those stories go away. So you know, the comparison I've

01:34:45.240 --> 01:34:49.600
[Guest]: been making more recently, I mean, the obvious comparison, of course, is with Erdogan because

01:34:49.600 --> 01:34:58.160
[Guest]: of the roots and religious nationalism support from the business class, the distance from

01:34:58.160 --> 01:35:03.640
[Guest]: secular elites and all of that. But another really good example, parallel is with Orban

01:35:03.640 --> 01:35:09.200
[Guest]: in Hungary. And what you have is when Modi talks about the car market consensus, and

01:35:09.200 --> 01:35:15.360
[Guest]: he talks about going against it, what he's basically doing is that he is pitching his own sense

01:35:15.360 --> 01:35:24.280
[Guest]: of Hindu authenticity against this supercilious, sneering, globalized elite. And it works.

01:35:24.280 --> 01:35:27.800
[Amit Varma]: And this is a framing that's actually common to all populists. Like I'd written a column

01:35:27.800 --> 01:35:32.560
[Amit Varma]: about it a couple of years ago based on Jan-Werner Muller's book on populism, where, you know,

01:35:32.560 --> 01:35:36.280
[Amit Varma]: blaming the elites is one of I think there's a whole laundry list of things that populists

01:35:36.280 --> 01:35:42.960
[Amit Varma]: have in common, whether it's Erdogan, or Modi, or Duterte, or whoever, or Orban. And one

01:35:42.960 --> 01:35:48.600
[Amit Varma]: of them, of course, is blaming elites. And you can't say that our elites haven't made

01:35:48.600 --> 01:35:50.040
[Guest]: that job easy for them, of course.

01:35:50.040 --> 01:35:54.600
[Guest]: Absolutely. I mean, it only works because there's a kernel of truth there. Right? People

01:35:54.600 --> 01:36:00.180
[Guest]: are supercilious people are I mean, I'll give you one example, right? The whole, let's say,

01:36:00.180 --> 01:36:07.280
[Guest]: if you are a religious Hindu, you're the entire conversation about the Ram temple outside

01:36:07.280 --> 01:36:11.920
[Guest]: of popular politics, if you look at it, the sort of newspapers, the if you look at the

01:36:11.920 --> 01:36:18.880
[Guest]: TV studios, and so on, the entire debate was dominated by people who just mostly just just

01:36:18.880 --> 01:36:23.840
[Guest]: are not very religious. They're just not they're not connected. They don't have a dog in this

01:36:23.840 --> 01:36:31.880
[Guest]: fight. And I think that this sort of thing, it breeds this tremendous sense of, of resentment,

01:36:31.880 --> 01:36:37.720
[Guest]: of being, you know, and I think that the lot of the BJP people, they, that's what they

01:36:37.720 --> 01:36:43.120
[Guest]: crave, they crave respect, what they don't understand is that you have to earn respect.

01:36:43.120 --> 01:36:48.000
[Guest]: And they think that they can, the only way to get that respect for them is to point to

01:36:48.000 --> 01:36:53.440
[Guest]: vote totals and say, look, now, I mean, again, it's totally illogical, right? I mean, you

01:36:53.440 --> 01:36:57.800
[Guest]: can get 303 seats in the Lok Sabha that but, you know, demonetization is still too crazy

01:36:57.800 --> 01:37:01.360
[Guest]: for Venezuela, I'm sorry. But that's not how they see it.

01:37:01.360 --> 01:37:05.480
[Amit Varma]: And it's something even Modi and peak bullshitting mode doesn't mention anymore, because it's

01:37:05.480 --> 01:37:10.240
[Amit Varma]: this kind of, that's not even a case to be made. You know, speaking about the BJP, if

01:37:10.240 --> 01:37:14.800
[Amit Varma]: we kind of look back through history and trying to figure out where they may go from here.

01:37:14.800 --> 01:37:20.320
[Amit Varma]: And one thread that I've kind of found in political Hindutva from the Jan Sangh onwards,

01:37:20.320 --> 01:37:24.920
[Amit Varma]: is that every leader has been made to look moderate by those who followed him. For example,

01:37:24.920 --> 01:37:30.120
[Amit Varma]: Vajpayee, you could argue, made Shyama Prasad Mukherjee look moderate. Advani made Vajpayee

01:37:30.120 --> 01:37:35.600
[Amit Varma]: look like a statesman. Modi made Advani look acceptable. And then came Adityanath and perhaps

01:37:35.600 --> 01:37:43.320
[Amit Varma]: now even Pragya. And do you therefore see the BJP getting more extreme, especially now,

01:37:43.320 --> 01:37:48.920
[Amit Varma]: with this consolidated hold on power, and the questions that are coming from certain

01:37:48.920 --> 01:37:55.320
[Amit Varma]: sources, which you know, I mean, I've heard people asking, ki mandir kaha hai? You know,

01:37:55.320 --> 01:37:59.560
[Amit Varma]: people arguing that Modi is too moderate, Adityanath is too moderate, we voted you to

01:37:59.560 --> 01:38:04.480
[Amit Varma]: power, mandir kaha hai? What do you think of the future direction of the BJP? Are there

01:38:04.480 --> 01:38:08.560
[Amit Varma]: competing forces pulling them in different directions? Or is this inevitable?

01:38:08.560 --> 01:38:12.640
[Guest]: So I think you could certainly make that argument for a progression the way you've made it.

01:38:12.640 --> 01:38:17.440
[Guest]: But I view it slightly differently. I think that there are always choices. And I think

01:38:17.440 --> 01:38:23.920
[Guest]: that the BJP in the Vajpayee era was in many ways grappling with those choices. You can

01:38:23.920 --> 01:38:30.160
[Guest]: fault Vajpayee for, you know, in the end, not sort of not doing everything that he could

01:38:30.160 --> 01:38:33.600
[Guest]: have done. But you know, there were certainly, you know, if you look at the kinds of people

01:38:33.600 --> 01:38:39.440
[Guest]: he surrounded himself with, people like Brijesh Mishra, people like Jaswant Singh, people

01:38:39.440 --> 01:38:45.640
[Guest]: like Arun Shourie. These are, you know, broadly people who were, you know, who wanted economic

01:38:45.640 --> 01:38:52.600
[Guest]: liberalization and had, you know, broadly liberal views on, you know, questions of faith

01:38:52.600 --> 01:38:57.280
[Guest]: and identity politics. And again, you know, as a conservative, it's not as though there

01:38:57.280 --> 01:39:03.160
[Guest]: are no problems there, right? There are problems on the sort of, there are problems that the

01:39:03.160 --> 01:39:07.240
[Guest]: liberal left in India has preferred not to look at, right? I once wrote a column in the

01:39:07.240 --> 01:39:12.680
[Guest]: Wall Street Journal about how this extremist Wahhabi cleric Zakir Naik was being hailed

01:39:12.680 --> 01:39:19.480
[Guest]: as a liberal by Indian liberals, which is preposterous. So I think there was a moment

01:39:19.480 --> 01:39:26.920
[Guest]: where the BJP could have turned towards a more moderate path. And that moment was not

01:39:26.920 --> 01:39:31.560
[Guest]: seized. Going ahead now, I have to say it's hard to be optimistic. You know, I've been

01:39:31.560 --> 01:39:38.160
[Guest]: in Delhi the last few days, talking to people and they point to the Gujarat experience.

01:39:38.160 --> 01:39:43.520
[Guest]: And they say that look, just as Modi as chief minister of Gujarat, when his his second and

01:39:43.520 --> 01:39:48.040
[Guest]: third terms, he kind of clamped down on the hotheads and so on, and that he's going to

01:39:48.040 --> 01:39:56.880
[Guest]: do that again. The way I see it, though, is that, you know, once you have unleashed these

01:39:56.880 --> 01:40:03.480
[Guest]: forces, and again, I go back to the Adityanath model, it's just, it's very difficult to put

01:40:03.480 --> 01:40:09.200
[Guest]: this genie back in the bottle. Now that they control the narrative, now that they have,

01:40:09.200 --> 01:40:13.000
[Guest]: you know, some of these sort of completely outlandish things, right? I mean, look at

01:40:13.000 --> 01:40:17.720
[Guest]: the, you know, if the, there's a point I made in one of my Times of India columns that right,

01:40:17.720 --> 01:40:24.440
[Unknown]: if the World Bank had an ease of doing bigotry index, India would be like, fastest moving

01:40:24.440 --> 01:40:30.600
[Guest]: country on that, right. So we went from being in the space of a few short years, we went

01:40:30.600 --> 01:40:36.680
[Guest]: from being a country where you could not even discuss things like Islamism and terrorism,

01:40:36.680 --> 01:40:42.680
[Guest]: right, the taboo topics, you couldn't even go there. And now we've reached a point where

01:40:42.680 --> 01:40:50.480
[Guest]: people on national television are propounding just like absolutely, you know, batshit crazy

01:40:50.480 --> 01:40:55.440
[Guest]: theories and ideas. I was on a channel the other day, on counting day, I won't take his

01:40:55.440 --> 01:41:02.560
[Guest]: name there. But we were having this discussion and Sabah Naqvi made the point, a perfectly

01:41:02.560 --> 01:41:07.520
[Guest]: legitimate point, that the kind of margins that people like Pragya Singh Thakur or Giriraj

01:41:07.520 --> 01:41:12.920
[Guest]: Singh Sakshi Maharaj had got, would suggest that this 2019 vote, in some ways is a vote

01:41:12.920 --> 01:41:16.680
[Guest]: for majoritarianism. It's a perfectly legitimate point, you can contest it, you can say it's

01:41:16.680 --> 01:41:19.960
[Guest]: also a vote for other things, but there's nothing wrong with saying what she said. And

01:41:19.960 --> 01:41:24.320
[Guest]: immediately you had other panellists, you know, attacking her in the most base terms

01:41:24.320 --> 01:41:28.840
[Guest]: and accusing her basically, because she's someone who happens to be Muslim, of launching

01:41:28.840 --> 01:41:35.480
[Guest]: a Ghazwa-e-Hind to subjugate and wipe out the Hindus. This is like, this is again, you

01:41:35.480 --> 01:41:41.360
[Guest]: know, some of it again, I mean, it's so crazy that it's funny. But it sort of tells you

01:41:41.360 --> 01:41:47.880
[Guest]: what has happened to the discourse. And because this has happened to the discourse, I see

01:41:47.880 --> 01:41:57.840
[Guest]: no will to discipline this, right? I don't see, what they want to do is image management.

01:41:57.840 --> 01:42:02.080
[Guest]: They're not actually willing to do something. And the best example of this is that, you

01:42:02.080 --> 01:42:07.520
[Guest]: know, the Prime Minister after Pragya Singh Thakur says that Nathuram Godse was a patriot.

01:42:07.520 --> 01:42:13.080
[Guest]: He says that, oh, well, I'll never forgive her. But if this is such a big deal for you,

01:42:13.080 --> 01:42:21.240
[Guest]: why don't you dismiss her? Right? So that's the point, right? There's image management,

01:42:21.240 --> 01:42:25.880
[Guest]: and then there's actual principle. And we've seen no evidence that actual principle is

01:42:25.880 --> 01:42:28.400
[Guest]: actually out there to trump image management.

01:42:28.400 --> 01:42:33.720
[Amit Varma]: I want to ask you one last question before we sort of end this episode, which is, okay,

01:42:33.720 --> 01:42:38.540
[Amit Varma]: now that Modi has got this resounding mandate, and now that we are where we are, looking

01:42:38.540 --> 01:42:42.560
[Amit Varma]: ahead to the next five years or the next 10 years, what gives you hope and what gives

01:42:42.560 --> 01:42:44.520
[Guest]: you despair?

01:42:44.520 --> 01:42:53.000
[Guest]: What gives me hope is that, you know, for all the problems, India's democracy has deepened.

01:42:53.000 --> 01:43:01.160
[Guest]: And that there is a possibility that India could just, in its own messy way, stumbled

01:43:01.160 --> 01:43:07.800
[Guest]: upon the right set of policies, learn from trial and error, at least there's a there's

01:43:07.800 --> 01:43:13.840
[Guest]: going to be a certain amount of political stability. And so he may be able to get the

01:43:13.840 --> 01:43:18.000
[Guest]: economic reform story right in the second term, but she wasn't able to be doing the

01:43:18.000 --> 01:43:21.840
[Guest]: first term. I'm not saying that will happen. But if I want to be hopeful, I'll talk about

01:43:21.840 --> 01:43:27.720
[Guest]: that. And I would also hope that the sort of natural fact that this is a deeply pluralistic

01:43:27.720 --> 01:43:35.760
[Guest]: society is going to prevail, and that people recognize that this is just not only morally

01:43:35.760 --> 01:43:41.040
[Guest]: reprehensible, but also insane, to try to sort of take 20% of your population and make

01:43:41.040 --> 01:43:45.800
[Guest]: them somehow feel as though they're not fully part of your country. So that would be the

01:43:45.800 --> 01:43:53.480
[Guest]: sort of optimistic side of things. On the pessimistic side, I think that there are quite

01:43:53.480 --> 01:43:59.680
[Guest]: possibly, you know, playing with things that have long term implications that they have

01:43:59.680 --> 01:44:03.720
[Guest]: not really figured out, right? I mean, these are really serious debates. Just the other

01:44:03.720 --> 01:44:09.080
[Guest]: day, I was reading a series of essays that Lala Lajpat Rai wrote almost exactly 100 years

01:44:09.080 --> 01:44:14.080
[Guest]: ago in 1924. Gandhi had just arrived on the scene. There had been riots between Hindus

01:44:14.080 --> 01:44:18.440
[Guest]: and Muslims in various parts of British India. And he was really trying to work through some

01:44:18.440 --> 01:44:23.840
[Guest]: of these issues, right? How do you work together as Hindus and Muslims and get the British

01:44:23.840 --> 01:44:30.280
[Guest]: out but also maintain some kind of good relations and so on. And one of the things that struck

01:44:30.280 --> 01:44:37.440
[Guest]: me was that we really no longer have people in the political class, with a few exceptions,

01:44:37.440 --> 01:44:43.600
[Guest]: right? There are people like Shashi Tharoor, even Jay Panda, who sort of read and are engaged

01:44:43.600 --> 01:44:52.360
[Guest]: with ideas. But by and large, the decline of the quality of our political class, right?

01:44:52.360 --> 01:44:58.800
[Guest]: Look at what was thrown up in the last 40 years of British rule. And look at what we've

01:44:58.800 --> 01:45:05.440
[Guest]: thrown up in the 70 years of our, of independence. The decline in quality has just been, it's

01:45:05.440 --> 01:45:10.680
[Guest]: staggering, right? I mean, you go from Ambedkar to Mayawati, if you just look at it in terms

01:45:10.680 --> 01:45:18.680
[Guest]: of intellectual content, for instance. So I worry that we now have, we're headed into

01:45:18.680 --> 01:45:25.080
[Guest]: an era where India is going to continue to face extremely large and complex problems.

01:45:25.080 --> 01:45:31.080
[Guest]: And we have a political class that may not be equipped to deal with those problems.

01:45:31.080 --> 01:45:35.000
[Amit Varma]: On that truly dark and depressing note, thanks so much for coming on the show, Sadanand.

01:45:35.000 --> 01:45:37.960
